<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 1600 GMT on July 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA -- Some 6,500 refugees have fled to Zaire and Rwanda
since last weekend due to ethnic clashes in the Cibitoke region in
northwest Burundi, the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees said Friday.
</P>
<P>
KATHMANDU -- Two people were killed and three wounded when an
electric transformer exploded Thursday night in a western Nepali
village, the official news agency RSS said Friday.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- The oath-taking ceremony of the new Afghan cabinet
scheduled for Thursday evening has been put off indefinitely owing
to differences between Prime Minister Gulbuddin Hekmatyar and
President Burhanuddin Rabbani over the cabinet list.
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- At least nine people were killed and seven others
injured when a car collided with an oil tanker in India's Gujarat
state on Thursday, the Press Trust of India reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
FREETOWN -- Rebels of the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) of
Sierra Leone have violated the cease-fire by raiding several
villages in the northern district of Tonkolili in the past few
days, defence officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South African Defense Minister Joe Modise
slammed the United States Thursday for its continued arms embargo
against his country, which he described as "irritating."
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran and Bahrain have agreed to stop propaganda
campaign against each other following Syria's mediation, an
official report said Friday.
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA -- Uganda has started a six-month offensive to wipe out
rebels of the Lard's Resistance Army in the north, The New Vision
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu will discuss a
U.S.-brokered "Lebanon-first" deal involving Syria and Israel with
President Bill Clinton next week, a report Friday.
</P>
<P>
PRAGUE -- Czech President Vaclav Havel Thursday reappointed
Vaclav Klaus as prime minister of a new three-party coalition
government, one month after Klaus lost his parliamentary majority
in the legislative elections. 
</P>
