<HEADLINE> UNHCR Concerned at Turkish Kurds Camp Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR) today voiced concern about the security of a
Turkish Kurd refugee camp in Northern Iraq, urging Turkish
authorities to put an end to recent jet low-level flyings over the
camp.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR spokesperson Ron Redmond stressed at a press briefing
that the Atroush camp was a civilian camp and not a guerrilla base
as was alleged and that his agency did not understand the purpose
of Turkish jets harassing it.
</P>
<P>
According to Redmond, four Turkish jets made several low passes
over the camp Tuesday morning, two of them flying about 150 meters
above head. They dropped during the flight six flares, with two of
them falling in nearby villages and four causing a grass fire at
the edge of the camp.
</P>
<P>
Despite a UNHCR call for Turkish authorities to exercise
restraint following the Tuesday incident, Turkish jets again
screamed over the camp Wednesday and Thursday, at height of less
than 100 meters.
</P>
<P>
The camp, which was set up two years ago, consists of about
3,000 tents, accommodating 14,000 refugees, 3,000 of them children
under five years.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR urged the Turkish authorities to put an end to these
incidents before any serious consequence occurs. Redmond said his
agency also worried about possible mass refugee movements out of
the camp and 14 families had already left.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR spokesperson stressed that the Atroush camp was not a
guerrilla base but ringed by military posts set up by local
authorities. It was five kilometers from the hills and it would be
difficult for people to move in and out of the camp in significant
numbers without being seen, he added.
</P>
<P>
Redmond said the UNHCR was willing to discuss with Turkish
authorities solutions to the current situation, including the
eventual voluntary repatriation of refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
