<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Unemployment Rate Down to Lowest Level in 6 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. unemployment rate fell
to 5.3 percent in June, the lowest level in six years, the U.S.
Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that businesses added 239,000 workers to
their payrolls in June following an even bigger increase of
365,000 in May.
</P>
<P>
It reported that virtually all of the increase in employment
occurred in the country's service industries and construction jobs
rose by 23,000. But manufacturing was weaker with a loss of 7,000
jobs, partly because of the impact of strikes.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate of 5.3 percent in June was the lowest
since it was 5.2 percent in June 1990. The rate remained between
5.4 percent and 5.8 percent in the first five months of this year
with a 5.6 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Reserve (Fed) decided this week to keep the
short-term interest rates unchanged and to see more data of the
economic situation although the U.S. economy expanded strongly in
the past six months.
</P>
<P>
But many analysts said the latest unemployment report made a
rate hike at their next meeting on August 20 a virtual certainty.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration, which is battling widespread
economic anxiety despite what is now the third-longest peacetime
expansion in history, has argued that rising productivity is
providing room for workers to enjoy higher wages without risking
worsening inflation.
</P>
<P>
But analysts noted that average hourly earnings, which are
closely watched for signs of inflationary pressures, jumped nine
cents in June to 11.82 dollars an hour. It was the biggest
one-month increase in this inflation barometer on record. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
