<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Reappoints Chernomyrdin As PM of New Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
Thursday reappointed Viktor Chernomyrdin as his prime minister
after scoring an election win, the Itar-Tass News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who was already back at work in the Kremlin for
another four years, asked Chernomyrdin to form a new government,
the Itar-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
With 99 percent of the votes counted, Yeltsin kept his lead of
more than 13 percentage points over Communist leader Gennady
Zyuganov in the second round of presidential elections held on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Central Electoral Commission at noon
local time (0800 GMT) showed Yeltsin winning 53.70 percent of vote
and Zyuganov 40.41 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a televised address to the nation, the 65-year-old Yeltsin
told the Russian people that his "new team" will have room "for
everyone."
</P>
<P>
"Let us not divide the country into the victorious and the
vanquished," he said.
</P>
<P>
The final count of the election votes is expected to take
several days to finish. Electoral officials said 72.5 million
votes have been counted. Turnout was 73 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
