<HEADLINE> Japan Welcomes Yeltsin Election Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese government leaders today
hailed the victory of Russian President Boris Yeltsin in
Wednesday's presidential election runoff and hoped the Russian
reform drive will not halt after the race.
</P>
<P>
Japan also hopes that Moscow will make efforts to normalize
relations with Tokyo, Chief Cabinet Secretary Seiroku Kajiyama,
the top government spokesman, told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed to seek to normalize bilateral ties in
the October 1993 Tokyo Declaration by resolving a territorial
dispute and signing a peace treaty, Kajiyama said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto voiced the hope
that Yeltsin's victory will secure continuation of the country's
reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto told reporters that Russia's finance and economy are
important to Japan while its defense and security will have a
bearing on the international community.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Ministry officials have said a victory for
Yeltsin will mean Japan does not have to change its stance over
its relations with Russia, especially over the long-simmering
territorial row.
</P>
<P>
The 1993 Tokyo Declaration calls for an early solution to the
dispute over four small islands off Japan's northernmost main
island of Hokkaido -- Etorofu, Kunashiri, Shikotan and the Habomai
group of islets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
