<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Press Lauds Mubarak's Role in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Sudan's independent Akhbar el-Yom
newspaper today lauded Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's role in
bringing leaders of 21 Arab countries together in their first
summit in the past six years.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic language newspaper said that Mubarak is the sole
Arab leader who can assemble the Arab heads of state at such a
pan-Arab summit, which was held in Cairo last month in view of
Israel's hardline Likud Party leader Benjamin Netanyahu's election
as the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
In a lengthy story that covered a whole page, the newspaper
said that the Arab summit would not have been held, had Mubarak
not been there managing to do it.
</P>
<P>
The summit restored the Arab League's prestige, shored up its
mission and reversed the league's theory of "frankness before
reconciliation to reconciliation before frankness," the newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
"We have to testify that President Mubarak has always spread
the noble demarche for clearing the Arab atmosphere, especially
after the right-wing Likud party assumed power in Israel," it
said.
</P>
<P>
Sudan's relations with Egypt were considerably improved at the
pan-Arab summit, held in Cairo on June 22-23. Mubarak was seen
warmly embracing his Sudanese counterpart Omar el-Bashir at the
Cairo international airport on June 22 before the summit convened.
</P>
<P>
In a related development Thursday, a high-level Egyptian
security delegation ended multilateral talks here with a number of
specialized bodies pertaining to the development of relations
between Egypt and Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Egypt had accused Sudan of harboring three terrorists involved
in a thwarted plot to assassinate Mubarak in Addis Ababa in June
1995, and Sudan had categorically denied the charge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
