<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Demands Another Six-Month Extention of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Burundian authority today
submitted to the Organisation of African Unity (OAU) its demand
for a six-month extention of the OAU Observers Mission in Burundi
(OMIB) and for its total strength to be raised from 60 to 118.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Burundian Foreign Minsiter
Venerand Bakevyumusaya admitted the situation at its border with
Rwanda, where Hutu refugees are fighting with the Tutsi-led
authorities, is "very precarious and even explosive".
</P>
<P>
The minister, who is in Yaounde to attend the ongoing OAU 64th
Council of Ministers Meeting, said the current fighting is
raising fears of an all-out civil war in Burundi, where aid
agencies put the death toll last year at about 30 a day.
</P>
<P>
OMIB's current mandate expires on July 15.
</P>
<P>
"That's why our government thinks another six-month extention
of the OMIB is critical to ensure peace and stability in the
country," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, before the opening of the OAU Council of Ministers
Meeting, the regional body is weighing the option of withdrawing
the military component of its mission in Burundi and only
maintain an OAU presence at the political level to monitor
developments and assist when the need arises.
</P>
<P>
OAU Secretary General Salim Ahmed Salim, in his report
submitted to the meeting, said the situation in Burundi, where
rebel Hutus have continued a rebel war with Tutsi-led
authorities, "will continue to degenerate year by year."
</P>
<P>
OMIB monitors the activities of the Tutsi-dominated army and
Hutu rebels in Burundi, where UN officials say they fear
bloodletting will break out at a similar scale to Rwanda's 1994
genocide.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bakevyumusaya told Xinhua that the Tutsi-led
government is also working on a power-sharing scheme with the
Hutu majority in a fresh bid for national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
"The government is for a political solution to the political
conflict," said the Tutsi foreign minister. "I'm a realist but
I'm fairly optimistic about the plan."
</P>
<P>
He said the forthcoming talks between the government and
various opposition groups in Tanzania's northern city of Arusha,
which will be presided over by former Tanzanian President
Nyerere, is "crucial" for the current negotiation process.
</P>
<P>
Bakevyumusaya said Burundian President Sylveste
Ntibantunganya, who will be in Yaounde to attend the OAU Summit
scheduled for July 8-10, will make an urgent call for the OAU and
international community to check the potential massive civil war
in his country.
</P>
<P>
More than 100,000 people have been killed in Burundi since the
1993 assassination of its first freely-elected Hutu president.
Burundi borders on Rwanda, where up to one million Tutsis and
Hutu moderates were massacred by Hutus in the 1994 genocide.
</P>
<P>
The OAU Council of Ministers is expected to issue a resolution
on Burundi. enditem


