<HEADLINE> Guizhou Starts Reconstruction from Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Two railways, which were cut off by
flood in southwest China's Guizhou Province, have re-opened and
the two other railway lines suspended are expected to re-open soon.
</P>
<P>
Water and electric power supplies have been restored to some
cities, and some businesses that were forced to close have resumed
in flood-stricken Guiyang city, capital of the province.
</P>
<P>
Floods caused by torrential rains that started July 1 have
flooded 59 counties in the province where 109,000 people have been
trapped by the high waters.
</P>
<P>
The floods also destroyed 17,270 houses, left 127,500 local
people homeless, cut off the province's major highways and
railways, and inundated 356,300-ha of crops.
</P>
<P>
Chen Shineng, governor of Guizhou Province, Liu Fangren,
secretary of the Provincial Committee of the CPC, and other
provincial officials visited the hardest-hit areas to coordinate
relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
Army troops and local residents also were mobilized to fight
the high waters and rescue those trapped by the floods.
</P>
</TEXT>
