<HEADLINE> UNHCR Not to Seek UN Secretary-General Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- High Commissioner for Refugees Mrs.
Sadako Ogata will not seek the position of the United Nations
secretary general, according to UNHCR spokesman Ron Redmond today.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Ogata already has a job taking care of 27 million refugees
and displaced people around the world, Redmond told a press
briefing.
</P>
<P>
"She says that she is not a candidate for the secretary general
position, she is totally concerned by her job taking care of the
world's refugees and intends to continue doing that," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Ogata, a 69-year-old Japanese professor, is highly
regarded in her current position in Geneva. She has been on a list
of candidates for UN secretary general that has been floated.
</P>
<P>
The other names are Kofi Annan, a Ghanaian undersecretary
general in charge of peacekeeping; Gro Harlem Brundtland, prime
minister of Norway; Mary Robinson, president of Ireland; and
Jayantha Dhanapala, the Sri Lankan ambassador to Washington.
</P>
<P>
The five-year-term of incumbent UN Secretary General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali will expire in December this year. He has declared
to seek another term, to which the United States has expressed
strong opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
