<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Economy Grows in Last Six Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's economy has been growing
over the last six months and inflation has been effectively
curbed, the State Statistics Bureau said.
</P>
<P>
According to the lastest figures released by the bureau, the
country's economy has been growing at an average rate of 9.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
The industrial and agricultural output increased 13.2 percent
and 4.6 percent from the same period of last year,
respectively. The output value of the tertiary industry rose 9.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese foreign trade continued to gain momentum at the
same time. In the first six months of this year, its total import
and export volume reached 7.87 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports accounted for 38 percent of the total, 16.5 percent
more than that of the same period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Vietnam signed 1.6 billion U.S. dollars worth of
contracts with foreign businesses in this period, bringing the
total sum to 21 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Vietnamese government has taken tough measures
to keep inflation under control. As a result, the prices fell
considerably and authorities predicted that the annual inflation
rate may be reduced to a one-digit low this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
