<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Judge Flies to Libya on Plane Explosion Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Seven years after a DC-10 aircraft of
the French air company UTA exploded above Niger, a French judge
today flew to Libya to conclude a lingering investigation of the
bombing in which Libya was suspected to be involved.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the daily newspaper Le Monde today,
Judge Jean-Louis Bruguiere, an examining magistrate of Paris, left
for Tripoli with about 15 police officers on board a chartered
plane authorized by the government.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Bruguiere, who has been investigating the
case, received a message from the Libyan government in May, which
said that he could start investigations on Libyan territory.
</P>
<P>
The UTA plane exploded on September 19, 1989 above Niger en
route from the Congolese capital of Brazzaville to Paris, killing
all 170 people on board.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary investigations showed that the explosion was caused
by a bomb in a trunk placed on board. No one has claimed
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
The French government has listed four Libyan officials as
wanted for possible conducting of the bombing. Among the men are
Abdallah Senoussi, number two of Libya's secret police and
brother-in-law of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi.
</P>
<P>
But Claude Silberzahn, director of France's security organ the
DGSE from 1989 to 1993, said in a book published in 1995 that
Libya's role in the case had not been "clearly established."
</P>
<P>
Libya is now under strict international trade embargo for its
suspected role in the bombing of the UTA plane and the bombing of
a Pan-Am aircraft above Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Libya denies having played any role in the two bombings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-05 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Land Transport between Jordan, Iraq to Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A senior Jordanian official said
here today that the volume of land transport between Jordan and
Iraq is expected to increase after an implementation of the
oil-for-food agreement between Iraq and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
In a statement here prior to his departure for home,
Undersecretary of the Jordanian Ministry of Transport Awadh
el-Tall said Iraq's imports of food, medicine and other basic
commodities through the Jordanian port of Aqaba will witness a
hike in the coming period.
</P>
<P>
Tall, who also serves as Chairman of Board of Directors of the
Iraqi-Jordanian Land Transport Company, said that a company board
meeting here Thursday examined means of developing the company's
operation and endorsed a future operational plans.
</P>
<P>
The company's fleet of trucks, which total 350 at present, is
also expected to expand to meet the rise in the volume of haulage.
</P>
<P>
The governments of Iraq and Jordan established the Amman-based
company in 1980 with a capital of 25 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, under the international sanctions imposed on it following
its invasion of Kuwait in 1990, has been heavily depended on the
land transport through Jordan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
