<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Considering to Redeploy Troops Around Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S military is
considering plans to move most of the 1,500 American troops
deployed in Riyadh, capital of Saudi Arabia, to a remote
desert air base to reduce their vulnerability to terrorist
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports today quoted U.S. Defense Secretary William
Perry as saying, "It is an urban area, it is the hardest area to
try to gain protection."
</P>
<P>
Perry was telling reporters traveling with him in his tour
after holding two-day discussions with Saudi officials on
investigations into last week's explosion in Dhahran that killed
19 American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States had under the consideration before
the truck bombing -- "moving some of the forces out of Riyadh."
</P>
<P>
Last November, a bomb, left outside a Riyadh facility devoted
to training the Saudi National Guard, killed seven people,
including five Americans.
</P>
<P>
After the bombing, Saudi authorities asked U.S. officials
to consider reducing the American military presence in Riyadh and
moving more forces to a remote air base in al-Kharj, south of
Riyadh, which had been used by the U.S. air force during the Gulf
War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Perry is expected to face harsh questioning next week when he
is scheduled to testify before two senate panels investigating
allegations that the Defense Department was aware of the danger to
American troops in Saudi Arabia, but had failed to take adequate
precautions out of fear of offending the Saudi government.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of the Senate Intelligence Committee, Senator
Arlen Specter, Republican of Pennsylvania, had said that he might
seek Perry's resignation over the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
