<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR, IOM Seek 7.6 Million Dollars for CIS Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR) and the International Organization for
Migration (IOM) today urged 7.6 million U.S. dollars for a pilot
program for managing the huge human movement in the former Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
A press release jointly issued by the two agencies said that
the program focused on improving systems and structures concerning
management of displacement and migration in the Russian
Federation, Ukraine and Belarus.
</P>
<P>
Projects will help local authorities and non-governmental
organizations (NGOs) integrate vulnerable and often destitute
refugees, internally displaced, formerly deported people and
people forced to return to their ancestral homelands by conflicts
in other Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) countries.
</P>
<P>
Many of these people are at present living extremely
precariously in a social and legal vacuum with nowhere to go and
no one to turn to, said the press release.
</P>
<P>
"Since the late 1980s, at least 9 million have moved to, within
or between CIS countries as a result of conflicts, environmental
disasters or a range of fears and complications arising from the
sudden and unprecedented disintegration of a single state -- the
former Soviet Union -- into 15 separate ones," the press release
noted.
</P>
<P>
The money called will fund the improvement and establishment of
reception centers in Russia, Ukraine, and Belarus, upgrading of
medical facilities, the building of reliable information systems
and personnel training.
</P>
<P>
The appeal, covering a six-month period up to the end of this
year, is the first step by the two agencies to follow up on the
guiding principles and Program of Action endorsed by a conference
on CIS human movement held in Geneva at the end of May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
