<HEADLINE> US-Japan Photo Film Talks Likely to Begin Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Negotiators from the United States
and Japan are most likely to begin bilateral talks over a photo
film trade dispute next Wednesday or Thursday, trade sources here
said today.
</P>
<P>
The talks, sought by the United States as the first step to set
in motion the dispute settlement procedure of the Geneva-based
World Trade Organization, would probably be held at expert level
between section chiefs of both governments, they said.
</P>
<P>
Washington filed a complaint with the WTO on June 13, accusing
the Japanese government of "unreasonable practices" that lock out
foreign products from the Japanese consumer photo film and paper
market.
</P>
<P>
At the core of the case is the U.S. firm Eastman Kodak's
assertion that its Japanese rival Fuji Co. has made deals with
distributors that exclude Kodak film from Japanese shelves. For a
year the two companies have been exchanging charges. Fuji
maintains that Kodak has pulled many of the same exclusionary
tricks in the United States.
</P>
<P>
If the bilateral talks under the auspices of the WTO cannot
find a solution in 60 days, an independent WTO panel will be set
up to judge over the case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
