<HEADLINE> Chinese President's Six-nation Tour Fruitful, Says Qian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The three European countries, though different in social
systems, ideology and economic development, have all been
attentive and willing to further long-term, stable, friendly and
cooperative ties with China on the basis of mutual respect,
equality and mutual benefit, and non-interference in each other's
internal affairs, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
The three nations in central Asia are newly-independent, whose
close relations with the Chinese people date back more than
2,000 years, mainly through the reknowned "Silk Road," he said.
</P>
<P>
China established diplomatic relations with these countries soon
after their independence and achieved rapid development in friendly
cooperation in many fields, Qian explained.
</P>
<P>
Developing long-term and stable relations with central Asian
countries are an important part of China's good-neighborly and
friendly policies toward its neighboring countries, he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
During Jiang's tour, more than 30 important bilateral documents
were signed, 18 of which were with the three central Asian countries,
Qian said.
</P>
<P>
"These documents further defined the principles and objectives
of developing bilateral relations and open new prospects for
cooperation in many specific fields including economic and trade
relations, jurisdiction and transport," he added.
</P>
<P>
Qian said China and Kyrgyzstan, which have more than 1,000
kilometers of common borders, signed an agreement on border
demarcation, which is of great historic significance.
</P>
<P>
It is yet another important document following the
Sino-Russian and Sino-Kazak agreements on border demarcation and
the accord on strengthening military trust in border areas
between China, and Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrghystan and Tajikistan,
Qian pointed out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
