<HEADLINE> China Optimistic About Sino-U.S. Relations: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- China said today it is optimistic
about future relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said, "I am optimistic about the
prospects for the development of Sino-U.S. relations."
</P>
<P>
Qian, who is accompanying President Jiang Zemin on a state
visit to Kazakhstan, said Sino-U.S. relations have improved
recently.
</P>
<P>
"Not long ago, the two sides reached an agreement on the
protection of intellectual property rights and other
issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Anthony Lake, national security adviser to the U.S. president,
is going to visit China and I will meet with (Secretary of State
Warren) Christopher in Indonesia in July when we attend a meeting
of foreign ministers of the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations," Qian noted.
</P>
<P>
"These high-ranking contacts will be conducive to the
improvement of mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. leaders have recently delivered separate speeches to
indicate that they attach importance to Sino-U.S. relations. We
have a high regard for these speeches and I am optimistic about the
prospects for the development of the Sino-U.S. relations," said
Qian.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States share common views on many issues
and have common interests. Of course, they also have differences
over several other issues, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe, whatever controversies and differences that may
exist between the two countries, they can be solved in a proper
way so long as both sides stick to the principles of mutual
respect, equal consultation, seeking common ground while reserving
differences, and non-interference in each other's internal
affairs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin is on the last leg of his
six-nation tour which began on June 24.
</P>
<P>
He visited Spain, Norway, Romania, Uzbekistan and Kyrgyzstan
before arriving in Kazakhstan on Thursday. 
</P>
