<HEADLINE> Turkey to Launch 'Turksat-1C' Satellite Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is expected to launch
`Turksat-1C' satellite from a base at French Guyana Monday.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, which has 16 channels, will cover a broader
area, embracing Turkey's links to the West and to Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
Turksat-1C will be replacing its predecessor "Turksat-1A",
which had gone off orbit after it was launched.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony for the launching of the satellite will be held at
the Turksat Base Control Center in Ankara's Golbasi district, and
the launch will be broadcast live on television across the country.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will be monitored from the center at Golbasi
and from the Middle East Technical University control center.
</P>
<P>
The new satellite, more efficient than the previous one,
requires less energy to operate, but covers a broader area. It
will enable telecommunications systems to be assessed more easily
by many people.
</P>
<P>
In addition to improving TV channel reception from Europe
and Asia, the satellite can be used for fax, data and
telex services in banks, airports and hotels, and for radio
transmission, education and diplomatic networks as well as for
national defense purposes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
