<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1.3 Million Killed by AIDS/HIV in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Joint United Nations Program on
HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS) reported today that HIV/AIDS-associated
illnesses killed 1.3 million people, including 300,000 children
under the age of five, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Of the adults, 600,000 were males and 400,000 females.
</P>
<P>
The UNAIDS expected over 3.1 million new HIV infections to
occur over 1996, or more than 8,500 a day -- 7,500 adults and
1,000 children.
</P>
<P>
The latest data showed that there are now 21.8 million people
living with HIV/AIDS all over the world. About 12.2 million of
them are men, 8.8 million women and 830,000 children.
</P>
<P>
Of these people, women account for about 42 percent and their
share is growing, the UNAIDS said, adding that the majority of
newly infected adults are between 15 and 24 years old.
</P>
<P>
The majority of AIDS cases occur before the age of 35, and over
90 percent of all AIDS deaths occur in people under the age of 50.
</P>
<P>
By June 30, 1996, some 1.4 million cumulative cases of AIDS had
been officially reported, a 19 percent increase over a year
earlier. The UNAIDS put the actual number of cases at over 7.7
million since the epidemic started at the end of the 1970s, taking
into account under-recognition, under-reporting and reporting
delays.
</P>
<P>
Since the epidemic began, around 28 million people have been
infected with HIV, 25.5 million being adults and 2.4 million
children. Of them, an estimated 4.5 million adults and 1.3 million
children have died.
</P>
<P>
According to the UNAIDS, 75 to 85 percent of HIV infections in
adults have been due to unprotected sexual intercourse.
Heterosexual intercourse accounts for more than 70 percent of
total and homosexual (male-male) intercourse for a further 5 to 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
Of all adult HIV infections, transfusion of HIV-infected blood
or blood products accounts for 3 to 5 percent, the sharing of
HIV-infected injection equipment by drug useers for 5 to 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the UNAIDS, mother-to-child transmission accounts
for more than 90 percent of all infections in infants and
children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0060 </DOCNO>
