<HEADLINE> UN Maintains Sanctions Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council today reviewed economic sanctions against Iraq and decided
that the sanctions regime remain unchanged, according to diplomats
here.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the council meeting today, Chinese Ambassador Wang
Xuexian said that the Chinese delegation urged Iraq to cooperate
continuously with the United Nations and fully implement the
Security Council resolutions concerned.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Chinese delegation suggested that the
Security Council evaluate the efforts made by Iraqi authorities to
implement the Security Council resolutions and relax the sanctions
against Iraq following the implementation of the resolutions, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We noted with satisfaction that the United Nations and Iraq
have signed a memorandum of understanding on implementation of
Resolution 986. We hope all parties concerned will overcome
disruptions and complete the preparations for the implementing
procedures so as to implement Resolution 986 as soon as possible,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador Edward W. Gnehm accused Iraq of not accepting
its obligations under Security Council resolutions, especially
blocking the U.N. Special Commission from inspecting certain
facilities in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
"The sanctions regime cannot be changed today. It will not be
changed until Iraq is in overall compliance with all of its
obligations to the council," he said. 
</P>
