<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Unemployment Rate Rises in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Canada's unemployment rate reached
10.0 percent in June, the highest level since October 1994,
Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
A drop in employment of 56,000, coupled with an estimated
36,000 people joining the labor force, pushed the unemployment
rate up 0.6 percentage points from May's 9.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Canada's unemployment rate had been relatively stable since
1994, ranging between 9.2 percent and 9.7 percent, the federal
fact-gathering agency said in today's report.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the job losses in June, employment growth had averaged
19,000 a month since July 1995.
</P>
<P>
The overall decline in employment in June fell
"disproportionately" on youths aged 15 to 24, it added. Youths
shouldered 38 percent of employment losses for the month despite
comprising only 15 percent of the total employed persons.
</P>
<P>
The youth unemployment rate increased 1.2 percentage points in
June and now stands at 16.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Quebec province accounted for 73 percent of the overall drop in
employment of the month, which offset gains made in late 1995 and
early 1996, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Canada's double-digit unemployment rate came at a time when
most analysts have been forecasting a stronger economic
performance in the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The overall increase in the jobless numbers makes it all likely
that the Bank of Canada will cut interest rates slightly to help
spark the economy, analysts here said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
