<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Arrears Problem Relieved: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African Unity
(OAU)'s serious arrears problem is being relieved with the
Council of Ministers meeting going on, a spokesman of the
regional body said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is getting better," said Ibrahim Dagash, press
officer of the OAU Secretariat, explaining that the number of OAU
member states under sanctions for serious arrears were reduced to
8 as of today from 13 before the opening of the ongoing 64th
Council of Ministers meeting.
</P>
<P>
They include Cape Verde, Equatorial Guinea, Central African
Republic, Guinea Bissau, Sao Tome and Principe, Gambia, Niger and
Seychelles.
</P>
<P>
Chad, the Comoros, Rwanda, Zaire and Djibouti have paid "a
good amount of contributions" of the OAU membership dues to
enable them to become "good members", he said.
</P>
<P>
Four countries whose economies have been virtually destroyed
by years of civil war, namely Liberia, Sierra Leone, Burundi and
Somali, are enjoying membership due exemptions.
</P>
<P>
Under OAU rules, member states placed under sanctions are not
allowed to speak or vote at OAU meetings until they pay up.
</P>
<P>
The OAU spokesman said this year's arrears of member dues
amounted to 11 million US Dollars out of the 1996 total
contributions of 27 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The OAU spokesman said the member states with heavy arrears
burdens have, during ongoing Council of Ministers meeting,
promised to step up the process of paying.
</P>
<P>
The 32nd OAU summit meeting is expected to be held here from
July 8 to 10, which observers say is the best time for African
countries to show their contributions to the continental body.
</P>
<P>
Some countries have had serious arrears problems for more than
10 years.
</P>
<P>
On question over whether the OAU would take more harsh
measures on the arrears issue, Dagash said: "We are weighing
options."
</P>
<P>
The arrears problem has limited the scope of functions of the
OAU which is eager to expand its roles over a number of regional
issues including peacekeeping and fostering of regional economic
integration.
</P>
<P>
The OAU is considering withdrawal or reduction of its
observers mission in Burundi partly because of the limited
operational fund.
</P>
<P>
In Liberia, the peacekeeping role is largely played by the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
And the first session of the Economic and Social Commission of
the African Economic Community (AEC), a key instrument in the
implementation process of the Abuja treaty which set up the AEC,
has been delayed time and again, mainly due to the lack of fund.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, OAU commended 13 member countries without any
arrears, namely: Algeria, Benin, Botswana, Eritrea, Ethiopia,
Ghana, Lesotho, Mauritius, Namibia, Senegal, Swaziland, South
Africa and Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
