<HEADLINE> UN Committee Urges Libya to Abide by Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Libya Sanctions
Committee today demanded that Libya refrain from further violation
of the Security Council resolution 748, which bans flights between
Libya and other states.
</P>
<P>
The Chairman of the Security Council Committee established
pursuant to resolution 748, known as Libya Sanctions Committee,
said in a statement that the committee considered the fact that
Libyan-registered aircraft flew from Tripoli to Cairo on June 22
and back to Tripoli on June 23. It also noted a press report which
said that the Libyan leader intended to fly from Tripoli to
Algiers in the near future.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council imposed sanctions on Libya in March 1992
for failing to surrender two men wanted in the 1988 bombing of Pan
Am flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, which killed 270 people.
The Libyan authorities maintained that the two Libyan suspects were
not involved in the bombing incident.
</P>
<P>
"The committee decided that the flights on 22 and 23 June, in
disregard of Security Council resolution 748 (1992), were serious
violations of the resolution," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The committee demands that Libya refrain from any further
violation, such as referred to in the above mentioned press
accounts" the statement said.
</P>
<P>
If further violation occurs, the committee would consider
recommendations to the Security Council on ways to strengthen
sanctions against Libya, according to the statement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Car Sales Continue to Accelerate in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Sales of new cars in Britain in June
increased for the third successive month, prompting hopes in the
industry of reaching the highest level for six years, according to
figures from the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders
(SMMT).
</P>
<P>
Sales in June were 141,266, 4.7 percent up on the same month
last year. That pushed sales for the first six months of this year
to 1,000,618, five percent better than last year and the first
time more than one million new cars have been sold in the first
half of a year since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The figures are the best news the motor industry has seen since
the boom of the late 1980s when sales peaked at 2.3 million in
1989, prompting optimism among motor industry executives about
prospects for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
Ernie Thompson, the chief executive of the SMMT, said: +After a
disappointing first quarter, we have now seen three months of
consistent market growth... (that) suggests that a two million
market can be achieved this year.+
</P>
<P>
Imported cars captured 62.2 percent of the market last month,
and 61.7 percent of sales in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Among companies to enjoy big increases in sales were BMW, Audi,
Daewoo, Fiat, Mercedes-Benz, Peugeot, Toyota and Volkswagen. But
both Vauxhall and Rover saw sales slip back. 
</P>
</TEXT>
