<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany to Withdraw From Satellite Project with France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Germany will withdraw from a
Franco-German joint project to build a military espionage
satellite "Helios II", German defense minister Volker Ruehe said
in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
"I don't really have enough money for this program," said Ruehe
in an interview with the German daily Bild am Sonntag.
</P>
<P>
"We will delay, push aside or cancel a number of (military)
programs. For example, I consider it more important to buy the
NH90 transport helicopters than buy Tiger combat helicopters," he
was quoted today by Agence France Presse as saying.
</P>
<P>
At a Franco-German summit in Baden-Baden in December 1995, the
two countries decided to jointly launch in 10 years "Helios II",
an optic observation satellite to be built in France with 11
billion francs (2.1 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
At the Franco-German summit in Dijon in June 1996, the two
countries said that they would re-examine their common armament
programs in order to save money.
</P>
<P>
But President Jacques Chirac and Chancellor Helmut Kohl said
then that none of the 27 programs under way be cancelled,
especially the "Helios II".
Germany has been cutting its military budget for several years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
