<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Afghan Cabinet Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISALAMABAD, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Six ministers of the new Afghan
coalition government were swore in today in Kabul, according to
reports from the Afghan capital.
</P>
<P>
However, nine portfolios, out of a full complement of 26
ministers in the coalition alliance, was announced by President
Burhanuddin Rabbani on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Wahidullah Sabawoon, intelligence chief of newly sworn-in Prime
Minister Gulbuddin Hekmatyar's Hezb-i-Islami group, was sworn in
as the new defense minister, replacing a Rabbani government
faithful Mohammed Yunus Qanooni.
</P>
<P>
Another top Hezb official, Abdul Hadi Arghandiwal, became the
finance minister under the terms of the agreement signed between
the two former arch rivals of Hekmatyar and Rabbani on May 24.
</P>
<P>
Qanooni, who was due to be sworn in as interior minister, was
however not present at the ceremony attended by the president and
premier as he was overseas to receive medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Shah Ahmadzai, the former caretaker prime minister,
officially became the country's new education minister, while
Qiamuddin Kashaf, a fellow member of his Itehad-i-Islami party,
was sworn in as minister for information and culture.
</P>
<P>
Sayed Ali Jawid of the Harakat-i-Islami group took the oath to
become minister of planning while a supporter of Rabbani's
Jamiat-i-Islami, Siullah Najibi, became minister of martyrs and
the disabled.
</P>
<P>
Hekmatyar in a speech at the ceremony pledged that his new
coalition government would remain united and avoid the bloody
mistakes of the past.
</P>
<P>
Hekmatyar promised that he and his former enemies would work
together to reunite the fragmented country.
</P>
<P>
"We are determined and resolved to preserve this unity that we
have created," the prime minister said in his first public
appearance since taking office 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
"The bitterness of the past will not be repeated and nobody
will hear any more news on discord and disunity in this
government," he said in Kabul's presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, eight people were killed and 26 others injured in
Kabul by rockets fired by the Taliban religious student militia
just before the oath-taking ceremony.
</P>
</TEXT>
