<HEADLINE> France Freezes Properties of Ex-Emir of Qatar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- France has frozen the properties of
Sheikh Khalifa Ben Hamad Al-Thani, former emir of Qatar, on the
eve of a visit by President Jacques Chirac to the Gulf emirate.
</P>
<P>
French presidential spokeswoman Catherine Colonna said that
Qatar's judicial authorities had asked their French counterparts
to freeze the properties of the toppled emir in France, and the
request had been met.
</P>
<P>
The amount of the former emir's properties in France was not
published, but it is known that most of his properties are in
Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Khalifa was toppled by his son in June 1995, and the
Qatar government has accused him of trying to stage a coup d'etat.
The ex-emir has been living in France since his overthrow.
</P>
<P>
Qatar is a big purchaser of French arms with 80 percent of its
armaments made in France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
