<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insurance Company Pays For Losses Caused by Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- China Pacific Insurance
Co. Ltd. (CPIC) has sent claims agents to flooded areas in
Guizhou, Zhejiang, Jiangxi and Anhui Provinces to pay benefits for
losses caused by recent floods.
</P>
<P>
An advance payment of 33,000 yuan was paid to several
businesses in Guiyang, the hardest-hit city in southwest China's
Guizhou Province, to help them resume production and aid their
employees.
</P>
<P>
CPIC's Guiyang Office sent 95 percent of its staff to handle
claims on location, and has personnel monitoring the floods 24
hours a day.
</P>
<P>
Lin Zhongjie, general manager of the Shanghai-based company,
left this morning for Hangzhou, Tonglu, Yuhang and other areas
stricken by torrential rains in neighboring Zhejiang Province,
where he will supervise claims work.
</P>
<P>
Since June 29, the northern part of the province has been hit
by persistent heavy rains, which resulted in the worst damage
caused by high waters in more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, company officials said the CPIC is working with the
Central Meteorological Station and the State Flood-Control General
Headquarters to track the flooding situation across China, and to
provide their clients nationwide with timely meteorological
information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
