<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Clinton Announces New Meat Inspection Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
announced today a new policy to revolutionize the inspection of
meat and poultry in the country.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the changes would be the most sweeping in the meat
and poultry industry since 1907 when a system of visual, touch and
smell inspection was put in place.
</P>
<P>
He said that as a result of an intense review, the U.S.
Agriculture Department will phase in a new meat and poultry safety
plan over the next several months.
</P>
<P>
The new inspection policy will contain these elements:
</P>
<P>
--Meat packing plants will be challenged to put new safeguards
in place at every stage of production "to make meat as safe as it
can be."
</P>
<P>
--Every slaughterhouse will be required to conduct scientific
tests to detect salmonella and the E. coli bacteria.
</P>
<P>
--Every meat facility will be required to meet high sanitation
standards.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton said that the policy change was resulted from
the fact that scores of people die and thousands become sick every
year through eating contaminated meat.
</P>
<P>
Clinton pointed to an outbreak of food poisoning in the Pacific
Northwest in 1993 when four children died because the meat they
ate was contaminated with the E. coli bacteria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
