<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Re-polling to Be Held in Pakistan-Controlled Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Partial re-polling in seven
constituencies and complete re-polling in one constituency of
Pakistan-held Kashmir will be held next week, the official
Associated Press of Pakistan (APP) reported today.
</P>
<P>
More than 1.6 million voters in the Pakistan-held Kashmir went
to polls last Sunday to elect 40 members of the Legislative
Assembly for a five-year term.
</P>
<P>
The election was held for 28 seats in the Pakistan-held Kashmir
and 12 seats for Kashmir refugees in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission has decided to conduct partial
re-polling in seven constituencies next Tuesday following reports
that polling process could not be completed in these areas due to
disturbances last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Complete polling will be held next Thursday in one constituency
where polling was stopped by armed clashes between two political
groups.
</P>
<P>
The administration has strengthened security in the region to
prevent repetition of any untoward incidents and ensure a peaceful
and smooth election.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Election Commission is busy compiling election
results of the other 32 constituencies, in which polling was
completed last Sunday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"We are in the process of receiving, recounting and compiling
of election results which were sent by the concerned returning
officers of the 32 constituencies, so that official notification
of the election results may be issued at the earliest," Secretary
of the Election Commission Syed Muhammad Akram Shah said here
today.
</P>
<P>
"Under the law, official notification has to be issued before
July 14, within 15 days of polling day of the election," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier APP reports, the People's Party of Azad
Jammu and Kashmir has won an absolute majority with 22 seats, with
the ruling Muslim Conference of Azad Jammu and Kashmir trailing
far behind with five seats.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
