<HEADLINE> Bakassi Crisis Leads to Inactivity of Fishing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian fishermen, forced to
inactivity since February, are complaining about decline in
production even if with the return of calm from the dispute
between Nigeria and Coumeroun over Bakassi peninsual.
</P>
<P>
A recent investigation has revealed that some fishermen who
abandoned their settlements and fishing gadgets have not returned
and those who have can not engage in deep sea fishing as was the
case before the crisis.
</P>
<P>
As the Bakassi peninsual has been declared military zone and
not much fishing could be done, Nigerian fishermen appealed to
the federal government and the international community to
expediate action on the crisis so that their only source of
livelihood would be restored.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian and Cameroun have clashed incessantly since 1994 over
the land dispute of the peninsula. It has been announced that
leaders of the two countries will meet and discuss the issue
during the Organization of African Unity summit scheduled for
July 8 to 10 in Yaounde, capital of Cameroun. 
</P>
</TEXT>
