<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Opposition Holds Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's opposition United
Parties attributes the country's huge national debt of 60 billion
Zimbabwe Dollars ( 6 billion U.S. Dollars) to the inability of
the ZANU PF government to come up with a forecasted economic
policy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a one-day inter-provincial executive meeting in
Harare on Saturday, United Parties (UP) information and publicity
secretary Isaac Manyemba said the delegates observed that the
economic situation in the country was worsening because the
government officials were corrupt.
</P>
<P>
"It is our view that this is due to the lack of forecasted
economic policy and the measureless corruption that characterises
every government department," Manyemba said.
</P>
<P>
He accused the government of being responsible for the fact
that most services are getting poorer while zimbabweans are the
fourth most highly taxed citizens in the world.
</P>
<P>
"It's either we have a situation where the interests of the
elderly, street children and destitute are taken care of by the state
or remove the high taxation because the government has done nothing
to show for it," Manyemba said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
