<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Regional Conference of Council of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- European regional conference of
Council of Hellenes Abroad (CHA) opened here today with a call for
unity and coordination amongst Hellenes living abroad in order to
achieve a solution to the Cyprus problem and promote Greek
national issues.
</P>
<P>
In his opening address to the conference, read by Cyprus
Foreign Minister Alecos Michaelides, Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides said that overseas Greeks have proved to be one of the
most fervent supporters of Cyprus' struggle for freedom and
justice.
</P>
<P>
The president noted that the presence here of about 77
delegates, representing over 1,000 Greek organizations from
Eastern and Western Europe, proves that the Cyprus problem is "of
primary concern to all Greeks."
</P>
<P>
Briefing the delegates on the Cyprus issue, President Clerides
said that the fact that the Cyprus problem remains unsolved for
nearly 23 years was due to "Turkish intransigence" and the lack of
will on the part of the U.N. Security Council and influential
countries to exercise pressure on Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey sent troops to
invade and take control of the northern third of the island
following a short-lived coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus president reiterated the government's position for
an overall approach to the Cyprus problem, saying that common
ground between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides must be found
before direct negotiations begin.
</P>
<P>
Clerides welcomed initiatives launched by different countries
in a bid to assist efforts for a solution to the Cyprus problem,
but stressed the need for coordination.
</P>
<P>
Andrew Athens, president of the CHA, stressed at the conference
the need for unity to promote the culture and principles of the
Greek nation and called on overseas Greeks to serve Cyprus and
Greece through "maximum participation and influence in their
respective countries."
</P>
<P>
The three-day conference will set up different committees to
deal with ethnic concerns, education and culture, youth, women's
issues, sport, social issues and Black Sea immigration.
</P>
<P>
Established in December 1995, the CHA is a world body that
unites Hellenes around the globe and acts as an advisory body to
the Greek government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
