<HEADLINE> International Container Shipping Center Developed in Zhengzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Zhengzhou's East Railway Station
has earned 480 million US dollars from transporting international
cargo containers since the city became a port of entry in January
1991.
</P>
<P>
The station, in the capital of central China's Henan Province,
has handled 3,792 standard containers with 650,000 tons of cargo,
which were exported to more than 80 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Located at the junction of the route between Beijing and
Guangzhou and the Liangyungang-Laizhou line -- China's two major
trunks -- the Zhengzhou East Station is the country's largest
cargo container trans-shipping base on the new Eurasia Continental
Bridge.
</P>
<P>
It handles more than 20,000 tons of cargo daily.
</P>
<P>
To expand its container shipping business, the station is
working to provide better service. Its cargo management system has
been computerized, thus enabling clients to check on cargo any
time in either Zhengzhou or Hong Kong. The station also offers
free temporary storage for clients' export cargo.
</P>
<P>
The station handled 17,000 tons of exports in the first five
months of this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
