<HEADLINE> OAU Members Adopt Common Stance at World Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- African countries will take a
common stance in the forthcoming world food summit to protect
themselves from being further exploited by the unfair
international trade system.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed in the resolution adopted here today by the
ongoing 64th Council of Ministers meeting of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) which is "deeply concerned" over the poor
food security in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"We will make our common voice heard at the summit to defend
our interests and objectives," said the oau resolution.
</P>
<P>
"Africa has the most strategic interest in the deliberations
of the summit and its outcome," said the resolution, believing
the summit provides Africa with a chance to, to a certain degree,
reverse the disadvantaged position.
</P>
<P>
In a world where 800 million people do not have adequate
access to food including 200 million children below the age of
five, Africa is the continent with the most serious problems.
</P>
<P>
"It is the only continent where agricultural production per
capita has been declining over the past 20 years," said the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
Africa is faced this year with an additional 1.2 billion U.S.
Dollar bill for cereal imports, with its cereal stocks having gone
down to four percent below the security threshold, leading to price
increases of 40 to 50 percent, according to a report released by
the world food program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
