<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death of First Professional Female Model in Lebanese Art </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Maryem Khiru, the first
professional female model in Lebanon's art history, has died
with her stories of courage and spirit of sacrifice for the
art.
</P>
<P>
Maryem died two months ago without attracting public
attention, when the country was immersed in sorrow for some 200
victims killed in a 16-day-long Israeli blitz in south Lebanon
in April, a Beirut well-known artist said.
</P>
<P>
"With silence, Maryem left, like that silence with which she
nudely sat in corners of successive studios to expose body
colors to generations of artists for more than half a century,"
Feisal Saltan wrote in a feature story published in today's
supplement of the Lebanese most-circulated An-Nahar daily.
</P>
<P>
The model's stories started with a painting, "the nude
Bedouin girl," produced by Kaisar Jemayel in 1939, and which was
shown to the public for the first time in the second salon of the
Parliamentary Building in central Beirut in the same year.
</P>
<P>
"This painting was only an attempt to retaliate a humiliation
in the cultural life in Beirut, which at a time was described as
anarchic, shameless and impudent," Saltan recalled.
</P>
<P>
"I was hesitant very much before I nudely sat in face of
Kaisar Jemayel, and I was shy at the beginning," Maryem said
several decades later, speaking of her first adventure. "And my
confidence increased when Mrs. Haik, Kaisar's girl friend,
appeared."
</P>
<P>
"My body had not grown completely yet, and I was only 16-year
-old," she added. "After some years Kaisar encouraged me to be a
model for painters and art students in the Lebanese academy, and I
did in 1945."
</P>
<P>
Kaisar died in 1958. "He had often drawn me and told me, Oh
Maryem, you are more and more beautiful and colorful, and you will
enter the history," Maryem said vividly. She became the first
professional model in the Lebanese University's Art Collage after
its establishment in 1965 and worked there until late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The idea of finding for himself a female model came to
Kaisar's mind when he was told on October 18, 1928 the murder of
his teacher Khalil Salib, a professional artist, and his wife
Kari.
</P>
<P>
Police found a painting of nude Kari in Salib's house during
investigations, arousing debates on morality in the tiny republic
under France's mandate at the time.
</P>
<P>
Kaisar had to wait for more than 10 years before carrying out
revenge for the humiliation of his teacher's death and the stern
opinion on the beauty of human body in his orient community.
</P>
<P>
"Kaisar was amazed at my Bedouin face," Maryem said. "And he
hid me under the table or the bed once the door of his studio was
knocked, in fear of any one seeing me."
</P>
<P>
"He gave me one Lebanese pound on every weekend, and I went to
him every day, sitting silently before him from 8 o'clock in the
morning until the evening," she added.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon endorsed its first official regulation on painting in
1966, recognizing the legitimacy of Maryem's job as a model in
the Art Collage of the Lebanese University, the only state-run
university in Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
