<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian President Accepts Government's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
today accepted the resignation of Prime Minister Pavel Lazarenko
and his government but asked it to stay on as a caretaker
government until a new one is formed.
</P>
<P>
The resignation was widely expected following the approval last
week of the republic's first constitution since gaining
independence after the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's new constitution, adopted on June 28 after weeks of
fierce debate, demands that a new government be formed within
three months.
</P>
<P>
Under the new constitution the prime minister is appointed by
the president but must be approved by a majority in parliament.
</P>
<P>
President Kuchma issued a decree yesterday appointing Lazarenko
as acting prime minister to head the caretaker cabinet before
parliament decides on a new head of government.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma has made it clear that he wants Lazarenko, a close
political ally, to remain as prime minister and has been holding
meetings with political parties to win their support.
</P>
<P>
Lazarenko, a former farm boss, was appointed prime minister by
the president on May 28 to replace Evegeny Marchuk who was sacked
for failing to ensure a stable and efficient cabinet and carrying
out economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's new constitution replaces a Soviet-era basic law in
force since 1978. It defines the roles of the Ukrainian executive
and legislature, which have frequently been in dispute in a bid to
gain the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
It also keeps the single-chamber parliament and introduces a
new yellow and blue flag and a new national emblem. It sets down
the right to own private property and entrenches Ukrainian as the
only official language in the country of 52 million people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
