<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Have More Ibises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A new way to rescue the rare ibis
from extinction has been found, thanks to artificial incubation
techniques introduced by scientists in north China's Shaanxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
Scientists in Yangxian County have made a breakthrough in their
experiments to artificially hatch ibis eggs and raise the young
birds.
</P>
<P>
The scientists, who work at a rescue center for the rare wild
ibises, remove ibis eggs from their nests, then supervise the
natural hatching process of the eggs and the development of the
nestlings.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, ten young birds have been artificially
hatched from eggs laid by three mother ibises. Scientists noted
that the new ibis moms, who previously produced eggs only once a
year, increased their egg production when they realized that eggs
had been removed from their nests.
</P>
<P>
The ibis was once common in China, Japan, the Korean Peninsula,
and eastern Siberia. However, its number has declined over recent
years, and now only about 100 live in the forests at the foot of
the Qinling Mountains in the Province.
</P>
<P>
The birds are under the top protection of the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
