<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quadrilateral Transit Trade Deal Signed in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan, China, Kazakhstan and
Kirgyzstan signed a protocol here today on a set of rules and
regulations on transit trade among them.
</P>
<P>
Under the quadrilateral agreement, customs officials will
follow a common set of documents at the entry and exit border
posts of the four countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement basically deals with a standard procedure
relating to the scrutiny of documents at the port of entry,
examination of goods, assessment of goods, loading of cargo and
movement in transit.
</P>
<P>
At the signing ceremony, Chairman of Pakistan's National
Highway Authority Shahid Aziz Siddiqui hailed the agreement as
historic, which will help to boost the economy of the four
countries.
</P>
<P>
He said the agreement will encourage businessmen from China,
Kazakhstan and Kirgyzstan to use the deepwater ports in Pakistan
via the northern parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Delegates of the other three countries said they expected the
agreement to go a long way to help strengthen the economic
relations between the four countries on the basis of mutual
benefits.
</P>
<P>
The four countries signed an agreement on transit trade among
them in March last year and the first caravan of vehicles with
transit goods is scheduled to move across the borders by October
this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
