<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Expects Greater Economic Growth in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is expected to witness a
greater economic growth this year than last year's 2.2 percent, a
World Bank report said here today.
</P>
<P>
If all policies and measures drawn to accelerate economic
development of the country are seen through, the report said, the
consolidation of fiscal stance would be more expansionary this
year than last year.
</P>
<P>
The country's manufacturing, construction and services sectors
would feel "a relative stimulus of the fiscal policy", the report
noted, but warning that economic activity would be hurt "if
movement through the ports does not recover soon".
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's ports are under government reform measures which
observers said would ginger up international trade.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank report saw no increase in petroleum production
of the country this year, a situation it attributed to the lower
allocation for cash calls in the 1996 budget, which is about 400
million U.S. Dollars less than last year.
</P>
<P>
The report identified "banking distress as another serious
concern for 1996". The number of distressed banks has increased
to 60, with "almost 50 percent of total deposit of the system now
held within distressed banks". 
</P>
</TEXT>
