<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Invites Arab Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar looks set to
encourage investors from the Arab world, especially from the Gulf
states.
</P>
<P>
A delegation led by the Isles' Minister for Planning and
Investments Ali Juma Shamhuna recently made an eight-day tour of
the Gulf states and Lebanon to market Zanzibar as a potential
trade centre for the eastern, central and southern African
mainland.
</P>
<P>
The local press said today that the delegation had appealed to
the Arab countries for revival of historic relations between the
two sides which date back more than a century ago to the monsoon
trade winds era.
</P>
<P>
The delegation briefed Arab enterpreneurs and government
officials on demarcated areas for export processing zones (PZ) as
well as incentives and guarantees for the investors.
</P>
<P>
The incentives include 100 percent ownership by foreign
entrepreneurs and 100 percent repatriation of capital and
profit and export-import duty exemption on corporate tax for the
first few years of operation.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, with whom Zanzibar has signed a trade pact, has shown
willingness to help Zanzibar in putting up the trade centre. A
Lebanese trade delegation is expected to follow up the issue when
it visits Zanzibar months later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
