<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Identifies Hong Kong's Competitiveness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A research study has concluded
that Hong Kong has powerful competitive advantages and a strong
base for its continued economic success.
</P>
<P>
The results of the eight-month long study were presented here
today by the project leader, Professor Michael Enright of the
Harvard Business School, who has carried out studies of
competitiveness in 14 different economies around the world over
the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Professor Enright said that the Hong Kong story is a story of
adaptation, resilience, and real market capitalism. In addition,
Hong Kong is well situated in the heart of the world's most
dynamic economic region.
</P>
<P>
He concluded: "If Hong Kong maintains and exploits its unique
attributes, its economic future ought to be as successful as its
past. I have confidence in Hong Kong's future and its ability to
influence the outcome of many of the uncertainties which it now
faces."
</P>
<P>
The study involved hundreds of interviews and an analysis of
key sectors in the Hong Kong economy. It focused on themes such as
human resources, technology development, cost comparisons,
internal competition and Hong Kong as a location for overseas
firms. The study findings will be compiled into a book to be
published early next year.
</P>
<P>
The research project was funded by a steering group comprising
a number of Hong Kong celebrities in business circles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
