<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Tourists Flock To Zanzibar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Zanzibar is becoming a
popular tourist attraction for Italians with the number of
visitors from this European country shooting up at an
unprecedented pace.
</P>
<P>
The number of Italian tourists visiting the Isles last year
was 8,922 compared with 4,345 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The figure is slightly behind that of Britons who numbered
10,391 last year in terms of trip to Zanzibar, according to
statistics released here today by the Zanzibar Commission for
Tourism (ZCT).
</P>
<P>
Most of the Italians flew directly from Milan on regular
charter flights and came to Zanzibar on package tours. They
stayed in hotels owned by Italian entrepreneurs who had put up
resorts in several parts of Zanzibar, especially on the east
coast and in the north of the Isles.
</P>
<P>
The ZCT said that Zanzibar received a total of 64,145 tourists
last year, against a little more than 40,000 received in the
previous year. The number is expected to shoot up to 70,000
this year.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the isles attracted other foreign tourists from
Germany (4,942), Australia and New Zealand (3,493), Scandinavian
countries (4,804) and Japan (876). There were also tourists from
the Far East, the Gulf states and some African countries, mainly
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The growth of tourism contributes more than 20 percent of the
Zanzibar gross domestic product (GDP). The ratio was less than
five percent in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Zanzibar plans to attract an annual 120,000 tourists by the
year 2000. More than 60 percent of investments in Zanzibar are
being made in tourism and other sectors related to the industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
