<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Model of Japanese Space Plane Tested in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- A model of a proposed Japanese
space plane was tested with a perfect landing at the Woomera air
base in northern South Australia state today.
</P>
<P>
Australian Space Office spokesman Graham Stanton said the model
was launched mid-morning today, and data will be recovered to plan
the next test, which will occur in three to four days if weather
permits, according to a press release available here.
</P>
<P>
The test series on the model, which is one-third the size of
Japan's planned reusable HOPE space shuttle, had been originally
due to start last Friday, but was delayed by technical and weather
problems.
</P>
<P>
Today's test, the first of up to 20, involved the model of the
proposed shuttle vehicle being lifted by a helicopter about 1.5
kilometers above the ground, about 2.5 km from the Woomera
airfield.
</P>
<P>
From there it was launched and tracked. Later, satellite and
microwave systems guided it back to the runway where it was landed
by computer.
</P>
<P>
If the tests prove successful, the HOPE shuttle will be used to
ferry cargo between Earth and the world's first permanent space
station, due to be assembled early next century.
</P>
<P>
The Woomera airfield was chosen from among 100 possible sites
around the world for a combination of its remoteness, former role
in space research and usually reliable weather.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
