<HEADLINE> Zambian Opposition Demands Repeal of Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Opposition parties are
still trying to repeal the constituion amendment adopted in late
May to bar former president Kennith Kaunda from contesting
presidency.
</P>
<P>
The Times of Zambia newspaper today quoted a joint statement
by heads of opposition parties as saying that the constitution
amendment should be repealed and then be adopted by a constituent
assembly through a national referendum.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement was a result of a meeting held by leaders
of 11 opposition parties in Lusaka on Wednesday. It has been
filed as an appeal with a certificate of urgency in the supreme
court.
</P>
<P>
Opposition leaders also insisted that this year's elections
should take place under the 1991 constitution.
</P>
<P>
They also rejected the registration of voters exercise as
carried out by Nikuv, an Israeli company entrusted by the
government, and demanded a re-registration be effected
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The inter-party liaison meeting called for the creation of an
independent electoral commission whose composition should be
acceptable to all political parties.
</P>
<P>
The controversial constitution amendment stipulates that only
indigenous Zambians are qualified to run for the presidency. It
actually deprives Kaunda of right to stand for the general
elections scheduled for later this year as the leader of
the opposition United Independence Party.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda's parents were immigrants from neighboring Malawi
before the independence of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
