<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Liberian Foreign Minister on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Liberian Foreign Minister H. E.
Sirleaf told Xinhua today that he was "cautiously optimistic"
over the peace prospect of his country, where ceasefire has been
holding following the recent factional fighting.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, a fresh ceasefire agreement was signed
between General Roosevelt Johnson's Krahan fighters and their
rivals, the "government troops" loyal to two other faction
leaders, Charles Taylor and Alhaji Kromah.
</P>
<P>
"I would say I am cautiously optimistic over the peace
process," said Sirleaf in an interview with xinhua in the
Cameroonian capital of Yaounde, where he is attending the ongoing
64th Council of Ministers meeting of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, reports from Monrovia say calm has returned to the
capital city of Liberia which was ravaged by the latest round of
street fighting between the "government troops" and their rival
Krahan fighters.
</P>
<P>
Liberia's faction leaders last August signed a general peace
accord in the Nigerian capital of Abuja, a development widely
believed to be a major step forward to bringing last peace to the
west African country torn apart by over six years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
However, the peace prospect shattered when a new round of
fighting and rooting occurred all over again in Monrovia starting
from April 6.
</P>
<P>
Sirleaf said the fresh ceasefire agreement does not contradict
to the Abuja peace accord. "instead, it's part of the
implementation of the Abuja accord," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister also confirmed reports that Johnson has been in
Accra since the latest ministrial meeting of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) held in Accra hosted by
Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings who is also the current ECOWAS
chairman.
</P>
<P>
On the question over whether the general was under "house
detention" by the Ghanaian government, Sirleaf said: "He will be
re-installed," referring to Johnson's dismissal from his post of
agricultural minister by the Council of State, the interim
cabinet in which Taylor and Kromah are vice-chairmen.
</P>
<P>
Sirleaf disclosed that five out of the six members of the
Council of State are now in Monrovia to discuss the situation.
Some of them had left the capital since the fighting broke out.
</P>
<P>
The minister said much would depend on the ECOWAS summit
meeting scheduled for later this month.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS has been maintaining its 10,000-strong peacekeeping
forces in Liberia, known as the ECOMOG, which Sirleaf said are
now "in full control of of the city".
</P>
<P>
On the question over what the Liberian delegation expect from
the OAU summit meeting, he said: "We are seeking moral support
here."
</P>
<P>
The minister disclosed that Wilton Sankawolo, Chairman of
Liberia's Council of State, will arrive in Yaounde at the weekend
to attend the OAU summit scheduled for July 8-10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
