<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Build More Concentrated Industrial Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam will build more concentrated
industrial zones in the coming five years, said Do Quoc Sam, the
country's Minister of Planning and Investment.
</P>
<P>
Eleven industrial zones will be developed in the north with a
total area of 1,690 hectares, the minister was quoted as saying by
the "Vietnam news."
</P>
<P>
Four others are planned for the central region, and seventeen
for the south with a combined area of about 2,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of Export Processing Zones (EPZ) and
industrial zones aims to concentrate industrial production in
areas that are consistent with the development of a master plan,
said Sam.
</P>
<P>
He added that this will reduce the cost of infrastructure
construction, better cope with managing environmental problems,
and create favorable conditions for management work.
</P>
<P>
So far, 17 EPZs and industrial zones in eight cities and
provinces were either granted investment licenses or approved.
</P>
<P>
Seven of the zones received domestic investment for
infrastructure development and another nine were being funded by
joint ventures with foreign partners. Only one was wholly foreign
invested.
</P>
<P>
Sam said that Vietnam will soon examine production, trade and
management in the industrial zones and especially the EPZs, which
emerged in the country in recent years and caused problems in
management control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
