<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese FM Fears More Convulsion in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz expressed here today his fear of additional "convulsion"
in the Middle East region in light of current deadlock in
the Arab-Israeli peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The peace process is witnessing a kind of cessation and
no one knows how long the peace process will be protracted,"
the foreign minister was quoted by the Beirut most influential
Sawt Al-Watan (Voice of the Nation) Radio as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The way has been lost," he said, "and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is attempting to alter what was
agreed upon in Madrid."
</P>
<P>
Refusing Netanyahu's recent proposal for the resumption of
peace talks without preconditions, the Lebanese government upholds
that the Middle East peace process should be based on the
U.N. Security Council Resolutions 242, 338 and 425, which embody
the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz pointed to an array of recent events, including a
military agreement between Israel and Turkey, convulsive
situations in south Lebanon and security incidents in some Arab
countries, fearing that "the region will witness more
convulsion."
</P>
<P>
He ruled out a quick formation of the multinational
committee to monitor a cease-fire in south Lebanon, which
is provided for by the cease-fire understanding between
Lebanon and the Jewish state on April 26.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the U.S., France, Israel, Syria and
Lebanon suspended their negotiations on the setup of the
cease-fire monitoring committee in Washington on the eve of
the May 29 Israeli general elections in which Netanyahu, leader
of the hardline Likud Party, defeated the Labor Prime
Minister Shimon Peres.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon as
suggested by an Israeli newspaper Friday, Boueiz expressed
doubt about the possibility.
</P>
<P>
Israel's only English-language Daily The Jerusalem Post said
that the new Israeli government should consider pullout from
Lebanon after security arrangements are made with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz noted what was suggested was a "treacherous and
provocative partial withdrawal" and Lebanon "will never fall in
this trap."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
