<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Decides Not to Accept Excess OECD Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 6 (Xinhua) -- South Korea has decided to reject any
unreasonable demand by the Organization for Economic Cooperation
and Development (OECD) for further opening its capital market, the
Finance and Economic Ministry said here today.
</P>
<P>
The OECD, the club of rich countries, is expected to submit to
Seoul a written questionnaire on South Korea's policy on capital
market and conditions for international investment.
</P>
<P>
The questionnaire will be in connection with South Korea's bid
to join the organization of advanced economies.
</P>
<P>
"If the letter asks us to open the capital market over an
unreasonable short period of time, we will emphasize the principle
of phased liberalization of the capital market since hasty
liberalization would lead to market instability and destabilize
the country's macro economy," a ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
The Seoul government, the official said, will make efforts with
the OECD for its entry into the organization by striking home the
South Korean position that Seoul will liberalize the capital
market as soon as the macro economic conditions allow.
</P>
<P>
So far, the OECD has asked South Korea to liberalize the bond
market, allow cash loans and permit friendly mergers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
