<HEADLINE> Cyprus,Britain Try to Solve Row over Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus and Britain are seeking a
peaceful settlement of problems that arise from the presence of
two British military bases on the island since 1960, said Cyprus
Foreign Minister Alecos Michaelides.
</P>
<P>
The minister was replying to press reports that the Cyprus
government was considering allocating Britain new areas for
British military exercises in Cyprus, according to the local
press today.
</P>
<P>
Michaelides said: "we are in regular contact with British High
Commissioner David Madden and the authorities of the bases for
various issues that arise with a view to deal with them through
dialogue."
</P>
<P>
One of these issues, he added, relates to the military
exercises British troops conduct in the Akamas Peninsula at the
western end of the island.
</P>
<P>
"As far as this issue and other issues are concerned, we are
on good terms and we hope we will be able to find satisfactory
solutions to all of them," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The Akamas Peninsula is one of the "retained sites" Britain
kept for its military purposes when Cyprus gained independence in
1960 after a four-year liberation struggle against the British
colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
British army exercises in this area have often been criticized
by environmentalist groups who say the natural environment was
badly affected by the military manoeuvres.
</P>
<P>
The two British bases of Akrotiri, on the south, and Dhekelia,
on the southeast, cover about three percent of the land area of
the island. British forces in Cyprus comprise about 4,200
servicemen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
