<HEADLINE> U.S. Plans to Move Troops to More Easily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 6 (Xinhua)-- The United States is planning to
move its troops from Saudi capital Riyad to a more easily
guarded camp in the kingdom in precaution against terrorist
attacks, according to local press reports here today.
</P>
<P>
A recent truck bomb explosion at the air-base of Dhahran,
eastern Saudi Arabia, killed 19 U.S.servicemen and wounded nearly
400 others of various nationalities.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry, who paid a two-day visit
to Saudi Arabia last week, reportedly said that the United
State was considering plans to move troops out of Riyad to a
desert air base south of the city.
</P>
<P>
The isolated site was believed to be more easily protected
against possible attacks.
</P>
<P>
Perry said that other contingency plans were also under
consideration for the possible movement of American troops in
Saudi Arabia following the truck blast.
</P>
<P>
"We are not planning a reduction of forces. We are not going
to cut and run from Saudi Arabia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last November a bombing in Riyad targeted at the Americans
killed seven persons, including five American nationals.
</P>
<P>
Some 1500 Americans are based in Riyad and about 3500 others
elsewhere in the Kingdom. The Americans are serving at a number
of bases across the country.
</P>
<P>
So far no timetable has been made known for the projected troops
movement.
</P>
<P>
The presence of the U.S. troops in the Gulf region has been
sharply criticized by Islamic fundamentalists who view the
United States as pro-Israeli foe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
