<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Develops Domestic Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's economic
powerhouse, is strengthening cooperation with neighboring
provinces and even with those economically backward ones in the
central and western parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
To promote trans-regional economic cooperation, Shanghai has
provided large amounts of capital, technology and information to
other provinces and regions. The move has not only improved
Shanghai's economic structure, but also boosted the economic
growth of other provinces and regions.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's economic cooperation with others has expanded
from industrial production to other fields such as real estate,
commerce, finance, transportation and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, the city reached agreements
with other provinces and regions on 18 cooperative projects in
commerce and trade, bringing the total trans-regional projects in
the sector to 236, which are expected to score an annual sales
volume of over three billion yuan this year.
</P>
<P>
The city's automobile industry has designated 66 automobile parts
manufacturers in 13 provinces, with a combined annual output value
of 3.6 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai-Bell Telephone Equipment Manufacturing Company, a
local giant in making telecommunications equipment, has had 28
components producers outside Shanghai, who supply nearly 30
percent of the components used by company.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is providing financial, information and technological
services for other provinces and regions. Last year, businesses
outside Shanghai accounted for more than 70 percent of the city's
stock and foreign exchange transactions, and the city
provided more than 6,000 items of technology, valued at 900
million yuan, for other provinces and regions.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has set up commercial businesses in all parts of the
country except the two provinces of Taiwan and Qinghai and the
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Market Report in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's tin, crude palm oil
(CPO) and rubber markets ended the week mixed with tin price
higher while CPO and rubber prices lower.
</P>
<P>
Tin price on Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM) ended higher the
week following strong buying interest. The metal surged 17 sen to
end the week at 15.66 Malaysian ringgit (about 6.26 US dollars)
per kg compared with 15.49 ringgit (about 6.19 dollars) per kg
last week.
</P>
<P>
Total turnover for the week rose to 800 tons from 561 tons
recorded in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The KLTM's price differential to that of the London Metal
Exchange ended the week at a premium of 35 US dollars per ton.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian rubber market closed the week lower on the
absence of fresh leads and poor market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
August RSS One fell 15 sen to end the week at 339 sen (about
1.35 dollars) per kg while SMR 20 eased one sen to 300 sen (about
1.2 dollars) per kg.
</P>
<P>
During the week, there were some inquiries from China but this
did not help lift the market sentiment. Dealers here attributed
the poor sentiment to a reserve of buyers and their wait-and-see
attitude as most European buyers were still away on long summer
holidays.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian crude palm oil physical market ended the week
easier on liquidation activities due to the absence of fresh
leads.
</P>
<P>
Dealers here said the market sentiment was dampened by news
that Indonesia would reduce its CPO export duty to 14.5 US dollars
per ton in July from 34.72 dollars per ton in June.
</P>
<P>
July South ended the week at 1,070 Ringgit (about 428 dollars)
per ton, 40 ringgit (about 16 dollars) lower from the price
recorded last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
