<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alleged Share Price Manipulators Acquitted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Supreme Court of Thailand has
upheld the acquittals by two lower courts of investor Song
Watcharasriroj and 11 others on charges of manipulating Bangkok
Bank of Commerce (BBC) share prices nearly four years ago.
</P>
<P>
The historic ruling on Friday closed the book on the first
share manipulation case ever brought by the Thai Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
Song, also known as Sia Song, and his co-defendants were
alleged to have colluded to buy BBC shares in October 1992,
causing the price to skyrocket. The Stock Exchange of Thailand
(SET) said 7,000 other investors were misled and joined the buying
spree.
</P>
<P>
Before they were charged in November 1992, Song and the other
defendants held about 45 percent of all BBC shares. But during the
past four years, they sold most of the shares and now hold less
than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Song said he, his relatives and friends had bought BBC shares
with the intention of taking over the bank because he foresaw its
growth potential.
</P>
<P>
About one year after Song's takeover attempts were aborted, the
former BBC executives began to make questionable loans.
</P>
<P>
The BBC now has a total of about 78 billion baht (3.12 billion
US dollars) in bad and doubtful debts.
</P>
<P>
Song and others also face three other charges on share
manipulation filed by SET.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the acquittal, SET President Singh Tangtatswas
said Sia Song has a lot in common with O. J. Simpson. In both
cases the general view was that the evidence for a conviction was
solid, but the court failed to be won over, Singh said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Gets Big Development in Horticultural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Transport and Energy
Minister Simon Moyo has said that the country's horticultural
industry proves the fastest growing of the agricultural sector in
the last 10 years, with an annual growth rate of 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
He told a meeting of the Horticultural Promotion Council in
Harare on Friday that an open-door policy had been adopted in a
bid to solve problems facing farmers who earned one billion
Zimbabwe Dollars (100 million U.S. Dollars) during the 1995/96
season from the European market.
</P>
<P>
He encouraged farmers to report and discuss operational
problems with the cargo carrier Affretair and other departments
of their concern.
</P>
<P>
As the sole shareholder of Affretair, the government is trying
to secure the acquisition of a DC-10 aircraft in time for this
year's peak export season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
