<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Rights Standing Committee Launched In Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Attorney-General Amos Wako
on Friday launched the Standing Committee on Human Rights to
investigate violation claims in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a statement Amos Wako said the 10-man committee is headed
by its chairman, the University of Nairobi's Prof Onesmus
Mutungi. Chelagat Mutai, former Eldoret North member of
parliament, has been appointed the committee's full-time
Secretary.
</P>
<P>
Amos Wako said the committee, which was appointed by President
Daniel arap Moi on May 22, last year, is completely independent,
and is not affiliated to any political party, including the
ruling party KANU.
</P>
<P>
The committee is expected to begin work in two months. It will
investigate complaints of violation of fundamental rights and
freedoms set out in the constitution, and will educate the public
on human rights and freedoms through publications, lectures and
symposiums.
</P>
<P>
The Attorney-General noted that it is the policy of the Kenya
government to promote and protect the rights of every citizen.
There is no country in the world where there are no human rights
violations, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
