<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: OAU Summit To Focus on Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- African leaders gather in Yaounde,
Cameroon, Monday to discuss the issues facing the continent, and
observers here consider that they would focus on Africa's
economic development besides stability.
</P>
<P>
1995 saw the economic growth rate of African states for the
first time surpass its population increase. And this year the
picture is brighter, with fine weather and good prices for primary
commodities. Some predict a five percent growth could be achieved
this year.
</P>
<P>
"Africa has recorded its highest growth in nearly a decade,"
and almost two thirds of the 48 countries in sub-Saharan Africa
grew by more than 3 percent in 1995 with three by 8 percent, and
eight by between 6 and 8 percent, according to a World Bank
report.
</P>
<P>
Regional cooperation has been on the upswing in the past few
years. With the creation of a regional telecommunication network
in 1995, the 16 States of the Economic Community of West Africa
(Ecowas) now enjoy direct telecom links without bypassing Europe
for connection.
</P>
<P>
The Trans-West Africa Highway Network has also been completed
linking by road all the capitals and major commercial centers of
the region.
</P>
<P>
In southern Africa, the 12-member Southern African Development
Community (SADC) has worked out a plan of action, consisting of
some 400 projects which needs 8.5 billion U.S. Dollars. Scores of
projects are being implemented to enhance regional cooperation in
the fields of agriculture, mining, transport and industry.
</P>
<P>
Two agreements signed recently have charted out strategies for
the conservation and utilization of water in the region and
closer coordination in the development of hydro-electric power
resources.
</P>
<P>
On March 14, the three presidents of Kenya, Uganda and
Tanzania signed a pact revitalizing the defunct EAC, opening up a
new chapter in east Africa cooperation.
</P>
<P>
It "will add an impetus to an establishment of a trading bloc
with 70 million people in the market place, which will attract
investment and stimulate industrialization process".
</P>
<P>
The three countries are discussing free trade, and free
movement of people and they reached agreement on the free
convertibility of the currencies of the three countries on July
1.
</P>
<P>
The three countries have expressed interest in incorporating
Rwanda, Burundi, Ethiopia, Eritrea and Somalia into the East
African Cooperation (EAC).
</P>
<P>
It is certain that during the three-day summit, African
leaders would discuss how to expand regional cooperation to
promote economic development in the continent so as to reduce the
risk of being marginalized in face of global economic
liberalization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: OAU Summit To Focus on Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The challenges are stern as
African leaders have to face the following hard facts:
</P>
<P>
1. From 1975 to 1994, per capita national domestic product of
48 sub-Saharan states had been down by 1 percent in average
annually while the east Asians saw an annual increase of 5.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
2. Debts up and assistance down
</P>
<P>
Debts of sub-Saharan countries in 1995 reached 223 billion US
Dollars, a five percent increase over 1994's, while official
development assistance was down from 16.7 billion U.S. Dollars in
1990 to 15 billion in 1994.
</P>
<P>
3. Africa's share of global manufacturing value added (MVA) --
the yardstick used to measure the manufacturing sector -- has
stagnated. The MVA of Africa was 0.7 percent in 1975 and it just
increased to 0.8 percent in 1994 while the MVA of other
developing countries had risen from 1.6 percent to 5.6 percent
over the same period.
</P>
<P>
4. Refugees in Africa topped 7 million, which is one third of
the refugees in the world, and the number of those displaced in
home countries are three times the figures who were forced to
flee their countries.
</P>
<P>
5. About 22 million people in Africa face the issue of having
food emergency as there are no signs of imminent improvement in
the food supply situation in the current year in sub-Saharan
Africa as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Aggravating the production deficit is a 50 percent rise in the
cost of imported cereals following a 9.5 million tons drop in
cereal output in sub-Saharan Africa compared to 1994, and
</P>
<P>
6. African economies stand to lose around 2.6 billion Dollars
annually with the increasing global liberalization of world
trade, according to U.N. Economic Commission for Africa head
Kinsley Amoako.
</P>
<P>
So the economic situation in Africa remains precarious and
worrying and contrasts sharply with the trends in Asia and Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the adverse impact of political instability,
ethnic conflicts and vagaries of weather, economic performance in
Africa continues to be characterized by low productivity,
inefficient management, failure to diversify from a narrow
production and export base and high vulnerability to the external
economic environment.
</P>
<P>
Most African states rely on a few primary commodities for much
of their exports, followed by beverages and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
Under this situation, African leaders have to put their heads
together and find ways to deal with the continent's economic
problems and socio-political stability so as to put Africans at a
par with the rest of the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Set Up Training Center for Eurasian Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has decided
to launch an international training center to promote economic
development along the New Euro-Asia Continental Bridge.
</P>
<P>
The training center, to be located in Rizhao City of the
coastal province of Shandong, will aim at promoting development of
human resources for countries and regions along the bridge,
according to a joint decision by the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation, the State Science and Technology Commission
and the State Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
The New Euro-Asia Continental Bridge, starting from China in
the east and ending in the Netherlands in the west, links more
than 40 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
China has attached importance to international cooperation on
development of the economic belt along the bridge.
</P>
<P>
An international symposium on the issue was held in Beijing two
months ago, with consensus reached by international organizations
and countries concerned.
</P>
<P>
The training center in Rizhao will provide training service to
technical and management personnel, officials and business persons
from China and other countries who engage in economic development
along the bridge, economic and trade cooperation, and exchanges in
the fields of science, technology and culture. The center will
also work to publicize various kinds of knowledge about the
bridge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
