<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Strives to Increase Tea Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Tea exports from India are
targeted at 600 million US dollars by the year 2000, almost twice
the present level, the Indian Express reported today.
</P>
<P>
A detailed presentation on the efforts towards this end will be
made to Commerce Minister B.B. Ramaiah by the end of the month, a
Commerce Ministry release said.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, Indian tea exports had declined to
about 150 million kilograms in 1993-94 (April-March) from 215
million kilograms in 1991-92.
</P>
<P>
This happened largely due to the collapse of the former Soviet
Union market which used to account for about 48 percent of India's
tea exports.
</P>
<P>
The tea exports target for the current financial year is 180
million kilograms, the release said, adding that the prospect for
the target is good because of the higher tea production this year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
