<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank to Order Bank Fund Injection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's central bank will order
the trouble-ridden Bangkok Bank of Commerce (BBC) to increase its
registered capital and to issue convertible debentures next week
as part of the efforts to rescue the BBC.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting this week with the Thai Bankers'
Association and the BBC Control Committee, the Bank of Thailand
will order the BBC to increase its registered capital by launching
2 billion baht (80 million US dollars) new shares at 10 baht (40
US cents) par, for 20 billion baht (800 million US dollars) next
week.
</P>
<P>
With the issue of new shares, the BBC's registered capital will
increase from the present 13 billion baht (520 million US dollars)
to 33 billion baht (1.32 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The move is aimed at helping the Central Bank rescue the BBC at
the lowest cost, according to BBC caretaker governor Rerngchai
Maraganond.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the BBC will issue convertible debentures to the
tune of 25 billion baht (1 billion dollars), with a coupon price
of 10,000 baht (400 US dollars) and a maturity period of five
years.
</P>
<P>
Rerngchai said the BBC control committee will form a syndicate
group to buy the debentures.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that as of May the BBC had bad and doubtful
debts to the tune of 78 billion baht (3.12 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Half of the sum was said to have been extended to politicians
on overvalued land as collateral, and the other half to BBC former
president Krirkkiat Jalichandra's own companies.
</P>
<P>
Investigations into the case still continue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
