<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fredericks Outrace Johnson in 200m </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Frankie Fredericks of Namibia
beat American world record holder Michael Johnson on Friday to win
the men's 200 meters final at the Bislett Games in Oslo of Norway,
snapping the American's winning streak of 21 races.
</P>
<P>
Fredericks, missed the world 100-meter record by just 0.01
Wednesday in Lausanne, Switzerland, clocked a winning time of
19.82 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, who set a world 200-meter record of 19.66 in the
U.S. Olympic Trials 12 days ago, was three hundredths of a second
behind on a chilly and rainy night at Bislett Stadium.
</P>
<P>
"I had nothing to lose," said Fredericks, who has broken three
African and Commonwealth records in 11 days. "I knew I could come
in here and get second and they would say: `well, we expected
that.'
</P>
<P>
"I had really no pressure. I knew that I'm going to run well if
I get a good start and that's what I did."
</P>
<P>
Johnson, meanwhile, had a terrible start.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody has their bad day," he said. "This was mine. I hate
to lose. When you give Frankie a lot of meters at the start you
have to lose."
</P>
<P>
Jeff Williams, another American, was third in 20.44 followed by
countrymen Alvis Whitted in 20.50 and Kevin Little in 20.57.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
