<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish Researchers Identify Common Cancer Gene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Swedish researchers have
discovered a gene responsible for the most common form of cancer,
a skin cancer called basal cell carcinoma.
</P>
<P>
Professor Rune Toftgaard, of the Novum Center for Nutrition and
Toxicology at the Karolinska Hospital in Stockholm, said today
that the gene is crucial for basal cell carcinoma of the skin.
</P>
<P>
Basal cell cancer, a benign form of cancer caused by sun
exposure, affects 200 people per 100,000 in Sweden, but up to
1,000 per 100,000 in sun-exposed countries such as Australia.
</P>
<P>
The identified gene, in the category of so-called tumor
supressor gene, is able to prevent unchecked cell growth. If it
fails, tumor growth is not prevented and a tumor can develop.
</P>
<P>
Toftgaard said further research will focus on using medication
to substitute the suppressor gene's function, as a means to treat
the skin cancer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
