<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Threatens Street Agitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 6 (Xinhua) -- The opposition Bangladesh Nationalist
Party (BNP) has threatened street agitation "if repression on the
party activities continued."
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen after swearing-in as a member of parliament
Friday, BNP chairperson Khaleda Zia alleged that "our offices have
been ransacked and our party leaders and activists harassed. If
this situation continues, we'll be compelled to take to the
street."
</P>
<P>
The BNP, the ruling party in 1991-1996, was defeated by its
arch rival the Awami League (AL) in the June 12 parliamentary
elections. The AL won 146 of the 300 parliamentary seats while the
BNP bagged 116 seats.
But Khaleda ruled out any possibility for the BNP to join the AL
government of Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina.
</P>
<P>
About the alleged rigging and irregularities in the election,
the BNP leader said that her party had already taken recourse to
legal steps seeking redress in the regard, and planned to form a
shadow cabinet in the parliament to make parliamentary democracy
more effective.
</P>
<P>
"We have struggled for democracy and restored parliamentary
democracy. So, whatever responsibilities we have been given, we
will perform those properly and sincerely," Khaleda added.
</P>
</TEXT>
