<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Visitors Greeted by Beagles at Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Olympic athletes and visitors are
greeted by sniffing beagles as they arrive at Atlanta's Hartsfield
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Hartsfield, like other 17 American airports, uses beagles to
help detect contraband that visitors bring into the country.
</P>
<P>
Leader, a 3-year-old beagle, and its partner Peppa, an
eight-year-old, are members of the Beagle Brigade, a unit of the
U.S. Department of Agriculture's Plant Protection and Quarantine
inspection team. They sniff for fruit, plants and meat that could
bring disease-causing bacteria and insects into the country by way
of international passengers' luggage.
</P>
<P>
If a bag has contraband, Leader or Peppa, with a pawing motion
or a stop next to the suspicious bag, alerts canine officer Steve
Manwaring.
</P>
<P>
On an average day, Leader and Peppa sniff from 1,500 to 2,000
bags. They work for about five hours and have a 90 percent of
accuracy. Once detected to have contraband, the visitor can be
fined up to 250 dollars.
</P>
<P>
One of Leader's biggest discovery was 80 pounds of salami
sandwiches in the suitcases of a Russian dance troupe visiting
Atlanta six months ago.
</P>
<P>
"These dogs can search about 200 bags in five to 10 minutes,"
said Manwaring. "They are a real tool. It saves a lot of time from
inspectors searching individual bags."
</P>
<P>
Three more beagles are due to join Leader and Peppa this month,
in time for the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Manwaring said the beagles are donated by animal shelters and
private owners and they are trained at centers in New York, San
Francisco and Miami for 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
It costs 2,000 dollars to train a dog, the canine officer
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
