<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Moves Closer to Single Currency With Lower Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Italy's month-on-month inflation has
eased to 3.9 percent in June -- below 4 percent for the first time
in 18 months, paving the way for the new Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi's push toward a single European currency.
</P>
<P>
Figures from Italy's national statistics bureau Istat showed
the fall from an inflation rate of 4.3 percent in May. And
economist said Prodi would be able to tame inflation to 3.5
percent this year and still lower to 2.5 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Prodi, a respected economist and former chairman of a giant
state holding company IRI, aimed to tame inflation to help bring
down interest rates and put Italy in a position to join a single
European currency in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Italy was widely expected to cut half a percentage
point of the discount rate -- a key bank lending rate which is now
9 percent -- if inflation falls to four percent.
</P>
<P>
But Italy's road to a single currency was far from smooth as
the European statistics bureau Eurostat said earlier this week
that Italy's year-on-year inflation rate -- though dropping from
5.4 percent to 4.4 percent -- was still not low enough to satisfy
the single currency requirements.
</P>
<P>
The currency standards require the inflationary targets for the
15 EU member states to be 1.5 percent above the average inflation
rate of the three countries with the lowest rate of price
increases.
</P>
<P>
From May 1995 to May 1996, the average rate of inflation for
the European Union as a whole had dropped from 3.1 percent to 2.7
percent, the Eurostat said.
</P>
<P>
Eleven EU countries presently satisfied the requirements but
Italy, Spain, Portugal and Greece still lagged behind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
