<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The followings are economic
briefs in Latin America in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico's exports will reach 91.5 billion
U.S. dollars in 1996 and rise to 104 billion dollars in 1997, and
the trade surplus will reach 6.9 billion dollars in 1996 and
diminish to 5.2 billion dollars in 1997, according to a report in
local newspaper "El Financiero."
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- Representatives of Ecuador's Petroecuador and the
U.S. Energy Development Corp. signed a contract Tuesday for the
joint exploitation of natural gas and prospection for hydrocarbons
in the Gulf of Guayaquil.
</P>
<P>
The project's investment will be 45 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- The World Bank announced a 75 million dollar
credit to four new projects in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The disbursement was made possible by the stabilization of
Brazilian economy and the improvement in the use of World Bank
resources, said World Bank representative in Brazil Marcos
Caramuru de Paiva.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The Brazilian production of mechanical capital
goods dropped 15.1 percent from January to May of this year,
compared to the same period of 1995, said the Brazilian Machines
Association (ABIMAQ).
</P>
<P>
The ABIMAQ said the total value of the production during the
five-month period was 5.96 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
ABIMAQ president Sergio Magalhaes said the government's
recessive measures are responsible for the present situation of
the sector.
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- Ecuadoran authorities announced Wednesday the lifting
of a ban on imports of bovine, ovine and caprine products and
byproducts of these animals established in April from the Southern
Cone Common Market, the Andean Group countries and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The ban was made when the country feared the contagion of the
"mad cow" disease originated in Britain that caused panic in the
world.
</P>
</TEXT>
