<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Wants Links with ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Mexico is interested in becoming
the first Latin American country to form a "sectoral dialogue
partnership" with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) in a bid to develop relations with the grouping.
</P>
<P>
Mexican Foreign Minister Jose Angel Gurria, who is on a
three-day visit to Thailand as part of his Southeast Asian trip,
told his Thai counterpart Amnuay Virawan Friday that Mexico is
seeking to be "a sectoral dialogue partner" with ASEAN as a first
step to closer ties between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Gurria said his country was keen on cooperating with ASEAN in
various sectors, such as energy, automobile parts, cement,
construction and machinery.
</P>
<P>
A sectoral dialogue partner cooperates with ASEAN in some
specific sectors such as trade, investment and tourism, while
being a full dialogue partner could cover political and economic
issues.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, Amnuay reaffirmed the establishment of
links between the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA) and the North
American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) to promote trade and
investment between the two zones in the future.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Gurria Friday, Thai Commerce Minister
Chucheep Harnsawat asked Mexico to allow imports of Thai rice
without waiting for a guarantee from the Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) that Thai rice does not contain fungi as
suggested by complaints from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Gurria had visited Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore before
coming to Thailand on Thursday. He is leaving Thailand for Japan
later today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
