<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Continues Investigations Into Ramirez Drug Empire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian prosecution
continues investigations into the alleged drug trafficker Luis
Enrique Ramirez as investigators searched the properties of the
drug boss across the nation in a bid to break his financial
network and identify his front men.
</P>
<P>
Investigators made at least 30 searchs in the past two days in
several cities, where Ramirez, nicknamed "Mickey," has businesses
and properties that are apparently used as a facade for his
illegal drug business.
</P>
<P>
Among the pieces of real estate searched is the famous
restaurant "El Buque," north of Santafe de Bogota. The boss of
the restaurant, Jean Ibrain Feghali, was charged with being one of
the kingpins of the Coast drug cartel.
</P>
<P>
Police also found that Ramirez owned many expensive weapons of
different calibers, which experts say are hard to get in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Ramirez was captured two weeks ago in a luxurious apartment
north of the capital and remains in the La Modelo Jail in Santafe
de Bogota.
</P>
<P>
Investigators ordered the detention without bail for Ramirez,
indicted for drug trafficking and conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
Under Director General of National Police Luis Enrique
Montenegro Rincon said that Ramirez was operating a drug
trafficking route between Colombia and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
A report by a Colombian intelligence agency shows that Ramirez
had 40 aircraft all over the country and was capable of
distributing four tons of cocaine a year from Brazil to Mexico and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Police said Ramirez began his drug trafficking activities in
1985. After the death of Pablo Escobar Gaviria, chief of the
Medellin drug cartel, he set up his own organization for illegal
drug business.
</P>
<P>
Mickey sent 400,000 dollars everyday to his two main
lieutenants, Liborio Baquero and Luis Antonio Rincon Gomez, to
launder the drug money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
