<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama to Reopen Talks on U.S. Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Panamanian Foreign Minister
Ricardo Alberto Arias said today that his country will resume the
talks with the United States on the extension of the U.S. military
bases beyond the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Arias told the press that the talks will reopen after the
Panamanian government concludes its consultations with the
political parties to reach a consensus on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The consultations, to be started today with the Arnulfista
opposition party, aim at finding a "national position" on the
matter, added Arias.
</P>
<P>
But Arias said that it will be difficult to adopt a national
position because of the different opinions Panamanians have on
this matter.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said he is exhorting all political and
social sectors to find a consensus on the "national position" of
Panama.
</P>
<P>
Arias declared that a popular consultation would be convoked
"only after Panama reaches an agreement with the United States in
the talks."
</P>
<P>
The United States has 10 military bases and 7,500 troops in
Panama. According to the Torrijos-Carter agreements signed in
1977 between the two countries, the U.S. military bases must
transfer to the Panamanian sovereignty by December 31, 1999, and
all U.S. servicemen will have to leave the Panamanian territory.
</P>
<P>
A few months ago, Panama and the United States began to discuss
the possibility of extending the U.S. military bases in the
Panamanian territory beyond 2000.
</P>
<P>
The talks were postponed when the United States warned that it
would not pay anything for staying in Panama. 
</P>
</TEXT>
