<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Concern About commercialism and Professionalism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Most of the Americans complain that
too much commercialism and professionalism in the Olympic Games,
according to a recent survey.
</P>
<P>
A large percentage -- 67 percent -- complains that there are
too many commercials on the broadcast although they won't be
frustrated to the point of changing the channel, shows the survey
of 1,002 Americans conducted by Marketing Research Services Inc.
</P>
<P>
Isaac Pitts, a counselor in New Jersy who was among those
surveyed, think the Games have been tainted by commercialism.
</P>
<P>
"It seems that all the athletes are getting paid to wear
somebody's logo," he said. "That takes away from what the Olympics
really represent. You want the athletes to represent your country,
not represent some company."
</P>
<P>
Dick Schultz, executive director of the U.S. Olympic Committee,
said that it wasn't easy for Olympic officials to strike a balance
between protecting the integrity of the Games and selling out to
corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
"To keep something like the Olympic Games on track, it's always
a little precarious. You walk a fine line and the ledge gets
pretty narrow and you can fall off quite easily," Schultz
said. "We've reached that fine line from a commercial standpoint.
You run the risk of overcommercializing to the point they become a
big commercial product and they lose their impact."
</P>
<P>
The public is nearly divided in the professionalism, with
slightly more Americans against participation by pro athletes, the
survey shows.
</P>
<P>
Fifty percent said professionals shouldn't be allowed to
compete, while 47 percent said they should.
</P>
<P>
Much of the public believe that the Olympics risks being
overshadowed by the all-star pros in basketball and tennis.
</P>
<P>
"I'd rather they be all amateurs," said Rick France, who was
also among the those surveyed. "I miss the days when people did it
just for the fun, for the love the of the game." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
