<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Urged to Disjoin Human Rights with Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Medium-sized countries are urging
bigger members of the World Trade Organization (WTO) not to link
trade with the issues like human rights, labor rights, or
investment policy.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister Amnuay Viravan made this remark
carried on today's local newspapers on his return to Bangkok after
attending a meeting of representatives of 16 medium-sized
countries in Switzerland earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
These countries called for some bigger WTO members to stop
applying "unilateral" action, Amnuay said, indicating it will
destroy the world trade system.
</P>
<P>
The Thai deputy prime minister said that the countries also
have proposed discussions on the issue during the forthcoming
meeting of WTO ministers in Singapore this December.
</P>
<P>
The discussions must take the form of consultations and not
negotiations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Guidelines should be set at the Singapore meeting, but they
should have no legal binding, Amnuay noted.
</P>
<P>
Compromise is needed when discussions involving specific
standards already applied by some WTO members are linked with
trade, he added.
</P>
<P>
Expressing optimism that negotiations in some sectors like
telecommunications and maritime transportation would be concluded
soon, Amnuay said that US complaints are holding up the talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
