<HEADLINE> Japanese Military Says Metal Fatigue Causes Chopper Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese Maritime Self-Defense
Force (MSDF) said Friday that metal fatigue in parts around the
rotor was the cause of a helicopter accident last month during a
joint military training drill around Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
Six people were slightly injured when an SH-60J MSDF helicopter
caught fire at the Barbers Point base on the Hawaiian island of
Oahu on June 18.
</P>
<P>
The chopper was taking part in an international joint military
exercise dubbed RIMPAC in the Pacific. The RIMPAC, for rim of the
Pacific, were launched in 1971 and are held every two years in
waters off the Hawaiian Islands.
</P>
<P>
The MSDF said metal fatigue in the parts caused the rotor to
spin off, forcing the chopper to lose control and setting fire to
its fuel supply.
</P>
<P>
The MSDF has suspended operation of some 56 SH-60J helicopters
since the accident. But they will be put into operation again
after technicians examine the metal parts in question.
</P>
<P>
Also during the six-nation naval maneuvers, participated by
troops from Japan, the United States, Australia, Canada, South
Korea and Chile, a Japanese destroyer mistakenly shot down an
American A-6E Intruder attack bomber.
</P>
<P>
The two pilots in the plane were rescued and suffered only
minor injuries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
