<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Warned of Poor Anti-Dioxin Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Greenpeace warned Japan on Friday
that the country's anti-dioxin policy is far behind those of other
countries.
</P>
<P>
The international environmentalists group is campaigning in
Japan to warn local residents of the danger of the chemical
compound and to call on the Japanese government to order a stop to
the production and use of the products which can generate dioxin.
</P>
<P>
Dioxin was a key element in the gas of Agent Orange the United
States used during the Vietnam War. The defoliant has been known
to cause cancer and deformities.
</P>
<P>
Dioxin can be easily produced by merely burning plastic
products. Officials said the Japanese health and welfare ministry
was alarmed by reports that high levels of the toxic chemical have
been detected in the air and soil near garbage incinerators in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
Researchers from a governmental anti-pollution committee
detected dioxin and other poisonous chemical products at sites of
industrial wastes at levels higher than allowed when they
conducted research last year.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the health and welfare ministry announced it would
review the existing guidelines for combating dioxin for the first
time in five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
