<HEADLINE> Graf, Sanchez to Vie for Wimbledon Women's Singles Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WIMBLEDON, ENGLAND, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion
Steffi Graf of Germany and her Spanish arch-rival Arantxa Sanchez
have eventually overcome their last hurdle and entered their
Wimbledon final, re-play of the 1995 Wimbledon women's singles
final.
</P>
<P>
World number one Graf has met with fierce opposition from the
12th-seeded Dimiko Date, who started slowly in all her matches at
the Wimbledon tournament.
</P>
<P>
During the first two set played on Thursday, Date, lost her
first set 2-6, launched powerful comeback upon her arch-rival and
grabbed the second set by the same 6-2.
</P>
<P>
When the Japanese player seemed totally dominated the Wimbledon
Center Court and forced the defending champion on the defensive,
the matches were suspended due to the falling of dusk.
</P>
<P>
At the crucial third set played early this morning, Graf, fully
recovered from her disadvantageous situation on Thursday,
overpowered the diminutive Japanese player and won the third set
6-3.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the match, Graf paid tribute to her tough
opponent Date, "Dimiko could not have played better tennis. It was
difficult for me to do anything."
</P>
<P>
"But at 2-2 in the third set, I was serving better than
Thursday and that made me feel better. I was a little lucky at
certain times but I played the important points pretty well," Graf
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kimiko Date admitted she would have preferred to
have continued playing on Thursday evening after wresting the
initiative from Graf.
</P>
<P>
"I wanted to finish the game on Thursday. I could have kept the
momentum going. My eyesight is very good and the fading light
didn't bother me at all," Date said.
</P>
<P>
"I knew I had to play my best as she is top player in the
world. It would have been difficult to beat her. I think she is
favorite to win the Wimbledon title," she added.
</P>
<P>
Sanchez Vicario cruised comfortably into the final Thursday by
beating Meredith McGrath 6-2, 6-1 in 61 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Graf aims for her seventh title at Wimbledon when she takes
Sanchez-Vicario on Saturday's women's singles final clash. Victory
for the German ace would also mark her 20th Grand Slam titles and
her 100th tournament triumph.
</P>
<P>
Graf defeated the fourth seeded Spanish player to win the
French Open last month. Sanchez-Vicario is the last person to beat
Graf in in a Grand Slam final -- at the 1994 U.S. Open Final.
</P>
<P>
Sanchez-Vicario has had a relatively easy passage through to
Saturday's final showdown. The Spanish ace will meet a seed for
the first time when she faces defending champion Graf.
</P>
<P>
The 1995 runner-up has only dropped one set en route was in top
form when she out-served, out-returned and out-ran Meredith
McGrath in her semi-final.
</P>
<P>
She and Graf will be meeting for the 36th time, with Graf
leading 27 win to eighth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
