<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Upward Trend of EU's Hard Coal Imports Maintained in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The upward trend of hard coal
imports into the European Union (EU) recorded in 1994 was
maintained in 1995, showing a rise of 5.4 million metric tons.
</P>
<P>
According to a Statistical Office of the Euorpean Communities
(EUROSTAT) report issued in Luxembourg today, the imports rose
from 131 million tons in 1994 to 136.4 million tons in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Among EU nations, the biggest import increase, 19 percent, or 3
million tons, was recorded in Italy, while the largest decrease,
17.6 percent, or 2.1 million tons, was reported by France.
</P>
<P>
In the coal producing countries, the import increase varied
between 0.8 million tons for Germany and 1 million tons for Spain.
</P>
<P>
The rise in imports is directly related to the increased demand
for hard coal from power stations.
</P>
<P>
The United States was the EU's major supplier of hard coal in
1995 with 38 million tons, leaving South Africa at the second
place with 30.2 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The two countries increased their exports in 1995 to the EU by
10 million tons and 2.7 million tons respectively in comparison
with 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
