<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Urges Belarus to Remove All Nuclear Devices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Russia today expressed regret that
Belarus has failed to dismantle and ship all the nuclear
facilities deployed in Belarus back to Russia as scheduled, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Viktor Esin, chief of the Russian Strategic Rocket Forces,
urged Belarus to dismantle and remove the remaining 18
nuclear-armed rockets to Russia before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Russian and Belorussian defence ministers agreed last December
to dismantle and remove all the nuclear devices, 81 in all
deployed in Belarus, to Russia before May 1996.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted Esin as saying that Russia and Belarus are now
working on a new schedule for dismantling and shipping the
remaining nuclear devices back to Russia.
</P>
<P>
The rocket army general said he hoped that Belarus will become
nuclear-free later in the year.
</P>
<P>
Russia, Belarus, Kazakhstan and Ukraine were the four former
Soviet republics which had nuclear weapons. Kazakhstan and
Ukraine have already disassembled and shipped all the nuclear
devices deployed in their territories and have become nuclear-free
states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
