<HEADLINE> Olympic Security Officer Shot in Atlanta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATLANTA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- An Olympic Games security officer
was shot in the chest by a stray bullet while standing guard near
the Olympic Village, authorities said Friday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Georgia State Olympic Law Enforcement
Command said Thomas Bentley, 43, standing guard at the entrance to
the Olympic Village, received a minor gunshot wound Thursday
evening by a bullet from an AK-47-type weapon fired from as far as
one mile away.
</P>
<P>
Bentley, from the Georgia National Guard, was rushed to the
Georgia Baptist Medical Center where he was treated for the wound
and released.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Bill Wells, said it was a random type incident.
"Someone shooting in the air is not uncommon on the Fourth of July
or New Year's Eve."
</P>
<P>
However, the incident, coupled with another early on Friday,
put Atlanta's Olympic security system on red alert at a time when
the Olympic athletes was coming.
</P>
<P>
Two guards narrowly escaped injury when two men driving a
stolen car crashed into a tent early on Friday at a checkpoint
near the equestrian venue, east cident sent the security to a red
alert though it was confirmed later to be a false alarm.
</P>
<P>
The organizers have put federal agents from the Federal Bureau
of Investigation (FBI) and other agencies, and thousands of
Georgia state and local police.
</P>
<P>
In preparation for the Games, security forces have conducted
crisis response exercises and security has been tightened in the
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
