<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Educational Advances in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, July 6 (Xinhua) -- Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region in
northwest China has come up with some impressive educational
developments.
</P>
<P>
The number of primary school student enrollments has climbed to
96.2 percent from 91.4 percent in 1985, and some 1,400 disabled
children now attend primary and secondary school, compared to only
a few dozen in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Over the past ten years, the local government has placed great
importance on improving the quantity and quality of its
teachers. More than 22,000 young people have graduated from
teacher training colleges since 1985.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100 million yuan has been spent on improving teaching
and study conditions at local schools, putting an end to the long
history of children from mountainous areas studying in cave
dwellings.
</P>
<P>
A series of measures encourage girl students to continue their
studies, in part by reducing fees or cancelling them.
</P>
<P>
Primary and secondary schools have been opened for local girls
of the Hui Nationality, along with special courses. The enrollment
rate of girls today has reached 90.96 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
