<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Perry Outlines Security Steps Taken since Bombings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Parry released on Friday a letter to lawmakers in an attempt
beforehand to dodge aside their oncoming attacks at the Defense
Department's lack of security measures resulting in a truck
bombing killing 19 Americans in a Saudi air base.
</P>
<P>
Perry is scheduled to testify before two senate panels
investigating allegations that the Defense Department was aware of
the danger to American troops in Saudi Arabia but failed to take
adequate precautions to protect U.S. servicemen's lives.
</P>
<P>
The defense secretary outlined in the letter security steps
taken right after the Riyadh bombing, that killed seven people,
including five Americans.
</P>
<P>
The letter, addressed to Strom Thurmond, Republican of South
Carolina, chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, goes on
to say that additional security measures have been taken since the
truck bombing last week, moving personnel away from exposed rooms
and installing blast-resistant material on military apartments.
</P>
<P>
Perry also says that the U.S. military is considering to move
troops away from Riyadh and other cities vulnerable to terrorist
attacks to some remote desert bases.
</P>
<P>
Republicans are seeking Perry's resignation over the Saudi
truck bombing and Perry is struggling to fight off their
accusations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
