<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cause of Record Number of Manatees' Deaths Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 5 (Xinhua) -- American scentists have found that
a toxin from red tide is the cause of a record number of deaths
among manatees in Florida state this year, New York Times reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Manatees have been listed as the species nearing extinction.
Scientists believe that only some 2,600 manatees remain in the
wild.
</P>
<P>
304 manatees have died in Florida since the beginning of this
year, exceeding by nearly 50 percent the previous record, of 206
in 1990, according to the Florida Department of Environmental
Protection.
</P>
<P>
Of the 304 manatees deaths, 158 can be attributed to the
red-tide toxin, scientists at the University of Miami have
concluded.
</P>
<P>
Red tide is a collection of algae blooms whose formation is not
entiely understood but it is linked to wind and weather patterns.
It carries with it toxin which can kill fish and other aquatic
life including manatees. It variously peaked and waned off South
Florlida's western coast since September 1994, researchers said.
</P>
<P>
The finding, announced on Tuesday, was described as a major
step toward saving the manatee from extinction. Since the cause of
the manatee deaths is a natural one, scientists are working on
possible solution to the problem. One idea being mentioned is the
opening of floodgates along rivers on the gulf Coast in Florida
state, allowing more fresh water into near-shore areas and
lowering the concentration of red tide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
