<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Denies Having Mercenaries in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- South African ambassador to Angola
Roger Tremer denied here today that the four South Africans UNITA
freed at its headquarters in Bailundo Thursday were mercenaries.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in an interview with a local radio, noting
that they are actually civilians, and not as UNITA claimed
mercenaries employed by the Angolan government.
</P>
<P>
Tremer said he was shocked by the way the National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) set the four South
Africans free by exposing them to the press.
</P>
<P>
UNITA has long complained that mercenaries, mostly from South
Africa, have not left Angola, alleging that about 4,500
mercenaries still stay in the country.
</P>
<P>
The four South Africans were captured in Angola's diamond area
in Lunda-Norte province in October 1995, and were found carrying
weapons which they claimed for self-defense.
</P>
<P>
Three of them said they were diamond miners while the other
admitted that he was employed by the Angolan government to
safeguard the safety of the diamond area.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, UNITA presented the four South Africans to the
media and then set them free. On the occasion, UNITA said three
of the men were mercenaries employed by South African-based
Executive Outcomes Company which is made up of former members of
the South African defense force.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the company was contracted by the Angolan
government to train its soldiers in the armed forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
