<DOCNO> XIE19960706.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-07-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Suggests Extension of UN Force in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Boutros Boutros-Ghali recommended that the mandate of the United
Nations Angola Verification Mission (UNAVEM III), the largest
peace-keeping operation of U.N., be extended for three months
until October 11.
</P>
<P>
He noted in his latest report to the Security Council that the
continued evolvement of UNAVEM III, which consists of 7,282
military persons and police officers, remains essential for the
peace process in Angola, particularly at this stage of the
implementation of the Lusaka Protocol.
</P>
<P>
Boutros-Ghali noted that both the Angolan government and the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) have
made progress in implementation of the Lusaka Protocol.
</P>
<P>
The positive developments include the adoption of the framework
agreement on military matters, the promulgation of the Amnesty Law
on May 8, the beginning of incorporation UNITA military personnel
into the Angolan Armed Forces (FAA), the completion of the
quartering of the rapid reaction police and quartering 50,000
UNITA troops as promised by UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
However, the parties have not fulfilled the time-frame agreed
upon between President dos Santos and Savimbi during their meeting
at Libreville on March 1, the secretary-general noted.
</P>
<P>
Continuing delays in the quartering of the remaining UNITA
troops, the high number desertions from the quarterings areas and
the incomplete withdrawal of FAA from forward positions all
require urgent corrective action if the peace process is to retain
credibility he said.
</P>
<P>
"The picture is no more reassuring on the political front. The
parties have yet to take a number of steps towards the formation
of the Government of Unity and National Reconciliation," he added.
</P>
<P>
If the peace process is to succeed, the parties in Angola,
especially UNITA, must show great readiness to implement the
commitments they have entered into, he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
