<HEADLINE> BA Pilots Plan All-out Strike Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- British Airways (BA) pilots and
flight engineers are threatening an all-out indefinite strike from
0400 GMT on July 16 unless the firm settles a pay dispute,
according to a BBC TV report today.
</P>
<P>
The strike could ground the BA fleet at the height of the
summer season. BA has said it hoped to avoid a strike but hinted
that it would bring in outside pilots to ensure that its services
continued.
</P>
<P>
The announcement from the British Airline Pilots' Association
(BALPA), which represents around 80 percent of BA pilots, follows
a 90 percent ballot in favour of a strike by BA flight crew.
</P>
<P>
BALPA said it was giving BA time to come up with a new offer
before taking action.
</P>
<P>
According to British law, BALPA only has to give the company
seven days notice of strike action. But the association said it
was giving extra notice because it was still willing to resolve
the dispute through talks.
</P>
<P>
The strike is over the relatively low pay of some pilots at
London's Gatwick airport and over inadequate pension provision.
</P>
<P>
A BA spokesman said its directors had met to discuss the strike
threat and the company had worked out a contingency plan to cater
for those hit by the July 16 strike. BA was most concerned to
protect customer interests, but would welcome further discussions,
he added.
</P>
<P>
BALPA said that a strike could cost BA 40 million pounds (62
million US dollars) a day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
